<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Olympic Champion Moceanu Gets Order Against Dad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. gymnast Dominique
Moceanu obtained a protective order against her father Monday,
amid allegations that he was following her and hired a private
investigator to document her moves "down to what I wear each
day."
</P>
<P>
"I'm in fear," Dominique told the press. "He was stalking me
from my school. He bugged my phone. Who knows what he's capable
of? I've lived with him for 17 years. I've seen how violent he
can be."
</P>
<P>
Dominique, who is in hiding in a Houston hotel with her agent
Janey Miller, went to the Houston courts in October to gain her
independence.
</P>
<P>
Her father resisted before granting it to his 17-year-old
daughter. Now, Dominique said her father, Dumitru, attempted to
hire someone to kill her coach Luminita Miscenco, and one of her
friends, Brian Huggins.
</P>
<P>
The father's lawyer said the allegations are false. Dumitru
was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
Houston police spokesman Robert Hurst said an investigation
was conducted into threats by "certain parties" involved in
Dominique's earlier successful attempt to become a legal adult.
</P>
<P>
Hurst wouldn't say who was investigated, because no arrests
were made.
</P>
<P>
There will be a hearing on December 9 to determine if the
order will be made permanent. The order forbids Dumitru from
communicating with his daughter except through his attorney.
</P>
<P>
A violation of the order could lead to the father's arrest.
</P>
<P>
Dominique was a member of the U.S. winning team at the 1996
Olympics and the winner of the all-around event at the Goodwill
Games this year.
</P>
<P>
She said she endured physical and verbal abuse while growing
up. "I used to get hit. Most of the time. My mother hit me
too."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
