<HEADLINE> U.S. Major Baseball League Umpires Lose Court Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Major Baseball League
umpires lost an attempt to collect more than one million U.S.
dollars in compensation for the strike-shortened 1994 season when
the Supreme Court refused to hear their case.
</P>
<P>
The court, without comment, upheld an arbitrator's ruling that
instead of receiving "special events" compensation because the
playoffs and World Series were canceled by the players' strike,
umpires were entitled only to that portion of pool payments
attributable to the All-Star Game a month before the strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
