<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIS Appoints Leadership of Financial Stability Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bank for International
Settlements (BIS) has appointed John G. Heimann as the first
chairman of the Financial Stability Institute of the BIS, the bank
announced Tuesday in the northern Swiss city of Basle.
</P>
<P>
Heimann will take office on February 1, 1999. He is at present
the chairman of the Global Financial Institutions at Merrill Lynch
&AMP; Co., Inc., and a member of the firm's Executive Management
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Frederik C. Musch is appointed as the institute's associate
director with immediate effect. He has until now been Secretary
General of the Basle Committee on Banking Supervision, a position
held since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Stability Institute is a joint initiative of the
BIS and the Basle Committee on Banking Supervision and was set up
in response to the need to strengthen financial systems worldwide.
Its early focus will be to promote better and more independent
banking, capital market and insurance supervision based on further
implementation of the ore Principles for Effective Banking
Supervision.
</P>
<P>
Interaction between the private sector, central banks and
supervisory authorities will play an important role in the
institute's activities.
</P>
<P>
Close cooperation with the International Monetary Fund, the
World Bank and with the Toronto International Leadership Center
for Financial Sector Supervision is envisaged.
</P>
<P>
The BIS hopes that the institute will over time broaden its
coverage to other areas bearing on financial system stability,
including the implementation of core principles currently under
development by international securities, insurance and payment
system regulators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
