<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Non-Proliferation to Top Sharif's Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif is to meet with U.S. President Bill Clinton in
Washington Wednesday with the issue of nuclear non-proliferation
expected to top the agenda of their talks.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is undertaking what the media here described as "a
crucial visit" to Washington in the "peculiar circumstances," and
the scheduled meeting between Sharif and Clinton is the first
formal one between the two after Pakistan's nuclear tests in May
this year.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that Washington's priority agenda during
Sharif's visit is nuclear non-proliferation. The visit was
preceded by several rounds of official and expert-level talks both
in Islamabad and Washington on nuclear-related issues.
</P>
<P>
"The dialogue has progressed well," Sharif said in a departure
statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's U.S. trip comes in the midst of allegations by Islamic
groups that he will "sell out Pakistan's nuclear capability to the
United States."
</P>
<P>
Qazi Hussain, head of the influential Jamat-e-Islami, has
warned the government against signing the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT) and vowed to foil "all conspiracies against the
national nuclear program."
</P>
<P>
However, Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed, who has
been holding talks with the U.S. on the non-proliferation issue,
said: "the speculation that the prime minister will sign CTBT in
Washington is totally baseless."
</P>
<P>
"We have not and will not barter away our security for economic
gains. There is no question of any compromise on Pakistan's
strategic nuclear and missile programs," Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, Clinton had offered Pakistan the
much-needed economic assistance provided it did not respond to
India's nuclear tests in May. However, Pakistan refused to listen
to the U.S. advice, triggering economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Unlike India, Pakistan, whose economy depends largely on
foreign aids, could not sustain the impact of the sanctions and
has agreed to adhere to CTBT by its cutoff date in September 1999
provided "the atmosphere of coercion" is cleared.
</P>
<P>
On November 1, Clinton ordered a partial lifting of some
sanctions against Pakistan which had been in place since 1990. The
U.S. decision also signaled that the International Monetary Fund
and the World Bank would revive their over one billion U.S. dollar
assistance program to save this South Asian nation from economic
collapse.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said recently that he wanted to revive the Pakistan-U.S.
relations to a level in the 1960s "when there were no unnecessary
pressure and sanctions against Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan took the nuclear road after India's detonation of a
nuclear device in 1974. When it achieved nuclear capability
despite the West's ban on export of related technology, the U.S.
stopped all military cooperation with Pakistan in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that Sharif will urge the Clinton
administration to remove all sanctions against Pakistan because
they eroded Pakistan's conventional capability vis-a-vis its rival
neighbor of India and created a "strategic imbalance" in the
region.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Islamabad expects progress in four issues
at the Sharif-Clinton talks.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan hopes Washington would make available some economic
packages to help its efforts at economic recovery and that
military sanctions imposed under the 1990 Pressler Amendment would
be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad also wants the U.S. to show high interest and get
involved in the settlement of the Kashmir Issue, which Pakistan
regards as the "core issue" between its relations with India, and
to offer an acceptable solution to the F-16 issue.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had paid 658 million dollars for 26 F-16 aircraft, but
in October 1990 the U.S. slapped sanctions over Pakistan's alleged
nuclear program and the planes were never delivered while the
first batch was ready in 1993.
</P>
<P>
For Pakistan, an acceptable solution to the protracted F-16
issue is either the return of the money or delivery of the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The News, a major English daily, said editorially that "the
people will expect the Prime Minister to deal with all the
critical issues in a manner which adds to the strength, stability
and welfare of the country."
</P>
<P>
"Realism should be the watchword during this crucial visit, but
no decision should be taken under pressure," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
