<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Panel Republicans Seek to Expand Probe to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Judiciary Committee of
the U.S. House of Representatives Tuesday opened a hearing on
perjury, while Democrats complained that the Republicans's abrupt
expansion of an impeachment probe against President Bill Clinton
lacked any legitimate purpose.
</P>
<P>
"Campaign finance has no relationship" to the sex-and-lies
report submitted to Congress by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr,
said Representative John Conyers, the ranking member of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
In his opening remarks, the committee chairman, Representative
Henry Hyde, did not address the abrupt decision to seek to
subpoena secret Clinton administration memos urging Attorney
General Janet Reno to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate the president's 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
"The committee has received information which suggests that the
campaign finance abuse memos may contain allegations of criminal
wrongdoing by the president," Paul McNulty, a spokesman for
Republicans on the panel, said Monday. "The committee is
duty-bound to investigate that information."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart questioned Republicans'
motives.
</P>
<P>
"The Republicans on the Judiciary Committee and the Republicans
in the House have finally come clean about what they're up to," he
said. "They have, despite all the protestations that this a
narrow, narrowly focused process looking at what was in the
referral, what it really is is a partisan process designed to
damage the president and investigate the president on any subject
that they see fit to go after."
</P>
<P>
Democrats said the move was proof of Republican desperation.
</P>
<P>
Hyde has "worked totally unilaterally, so it's very clear that
this is a partisan witch hunt that he's determined to ram through
as quickly as he can," Conyers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Conyers spoke just after Republicans, who control the Judiciary
Committee 21-16, prepared to subpoena FBI Director Louis Freeh and
federal prosecutor Charles LaBella and gain access to their secret
memos laying out Clinton's alleged fund-raising irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Hyde and other Republicans planned to seek subpoenas in closed
session after the perjury hearing.
</P>
<P>
Republicans had intended for Tuesday's hearing on "the
consequences of perjury and related crimes" to underscore
Clinton's refusal to admit he lied about his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
The committee's agenda included testimony from legal experts
and military officials, and two witnesses punished for lying about
sex in civil lawsuits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
