<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French, German Pharmaceutical Groups Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The French bio-pharmaceutical
group Rhone-Poulenc and its German counterpart Hoechst Tuesday
said they will merge the life science part of their groups into a
new company called Aventis.
</P>
<P>
Rhone-Poulenc president Jean-Rene Fourtou and Hoechst president
Jurgen Dormann made the announcement during the Franco-German
summit being held in Potsdam by President Jacques Chirac and
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
``We want to create a new company, with European roots and
global reach, to take full advantage of the extensive
opportunities of life sciences in the 21st century,''said the
leaders of the two companies in a communique.
</P>
<P>
Aventis, which will be incorporated in France and based in
Strasbourg, will be the world's number two life sciences producers
after the Swiss Novartis, after the merger is completed by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Both Rhone-Poulenc and Hoechst will hold half of the new
company's stocks, while Dormann will be the president of the board
of management of Aventis, and Fourtous its vice president.
</P>
<P>
Aventis is expected to employ 95,000 people, have a 20 billion
U.S. dollar sales figures and be the world leader in life
sciences, holding top positions in both pharmaceuticals and
agriculture, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
It said that with an annual research budget of 3 billion U.S.
dollars, Aventis will have one of the best innovative capabilities
in the industry.
</P>
<P>
No plan to lay off employees was announced in the communique.
</P>
<P>
The merger between Rhone-Poulenc and Hoechst has become a part
of the wave of mergers engulfing international corporations around
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
