<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Get $474 Million From IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's 6th letter of Intent
will lead to the next tranche of 474 million U.S. dollars from the
17.2-billion-dollar IMF rescue package, Finance Minister Tarin
Nimmanhaeminda said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tarin said after a cabinet meeting that the cabinet had
approved the letter and it would then be forwarded to the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The letter is expected to get the final stamp of approval from
the IMF Board in Washington between December 14-15. The next
tranche of loan will be disbursed a few days after that.
</P>
<P>
Of all the 474 million dollars, 135 million dollars would come
directly from the IMF and the rest of it would be from other
countries in the program.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent released here said Thailand will nearly
double its budget deficit to 5 percent of the GDP in an effort to
help ease the liquidity crunch. Tarin said the new agreement
allows the government to inject 250 billion baht (6.9 billion
dollars), the equivalent of 5 percent of GDP, into the economy.
</P>
<P>
The document said the country is likely to record 7-8 percent
economic contraction this year while it will record 1 percent
growth next year. The foreign reserves were expected to rise to
32-34 billion dollars at the end of 1999 from the current 28.6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has suffered its worst-ever economic slump in decades
after the collapse of its financial system. The country
depreciated the baht in July 1997 and entered the IMF program in
August the same year. So far 12 billion dollars has been
disbursed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
