<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Calls for Justice for Holocaust Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright called on an international conference on the
fate of Nazi-looted art and property Tuesday to seek justice for
the victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal must be justice," Albright told the conference, which
opened on Monday night at the Holocaust Museum in Washington. The
meeting was attended by more than 40 countries and organizations.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference is sponsored by the Museum and the U.S.
State Department.
</P>
<P>
Albright called on all archives around the world to be fully
open to researchers. She didn't mention any country by name nor
did she cite the Vatican, which has refused to open its files.
</P>
<P>
"We must dig to find the truth," she said. "Only by knowing and
being honest about the past can we gain peace in the present and
confidence in the future," she told conference delegates.
</P>
<P>
"Remaining Holocaust survivors have reached an advance stage in
life," said she, stressing the urgency of the problems.
</P>
<P>
Albright recalled that she learned only last year that her
Czech grandparents and other relatives had been killed by Nazi
Germany during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the conference is both about material and moral
matters and she urged delegates to reach consensus on making
restitution for Nazi- looted goods and on educating the public.
</P>
<P>
"It is about much more than gold and art and insurance," she
said. "It's about remembering that no one's blood is less or more
precious than our own."
</P>
<P>
Delegates are dealing with material and moral questions from a
period in which Nazi Germany killed six million Jews and looted
billions of dollars in gold, art and private and communal property
across Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
