<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exxon, Mobil Agree to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. oil giants Exxon and
Mobil announced here on Tuesday that they agreed to a 77.2 billion
U.S. dollar merger deal, the largest industrial merger case
leading to the creation of the world's number one energy company.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the two companies said: "This merger will
enhance our ability to be an effective global competitor in a
volatile world economy and in an industry that is more and more
competitive."
</P>
<P>
Exxon and Mobil have a market value of 177 billion U.S. dollars
and 61 billion dollars respectively. Their combined market value
will be well above that of Royal Dutch/Shell Group, currently the
world's largest oil and gas company.
</P>
<P>
Exxon and Mobil have a total of over 120,000 employees and a
revenue of 200 billion dollars in 1997, involving in oil and
natural gas exploration, extraction, refining, chemicals
production and retailing in more than 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
The merger agreement came four days after the two companies
confirmed that their merger talks were continuing. The action was
taken under the worsening situation of low oil prices amid low
demand as a result of the contagion of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Exxon and Mobil, forecast to face a drastic fall in their
earnings this year, are trying to save costs through the
combination.
</P>
<P>
The deal, under which Exxon will acquire Mobil, tops British
Petroleum's planned 58.5 billion dollar purchase of U.S. Amoco as
the largest industrial merger.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the move would herald similar acquisitions in the
oil industry and would change the scenario of the world energy
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 270,000 Angolans HIV Positive: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- There are 270,000 HIV positive
people in Angola, Angolan Deputy Health Minister Teresa Cohen
said here Tuesday, on the World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
"The figure shows how serious the situation is in Angola" with
a population of 10 million people, said the deputy minister.
</P>
<P>
Cohen stressed that the level of people's living and education
is greatly linked with their sufferings from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
She called upon the Angolan government to go all out to put
people's education on AIDS prevention as priority.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister announced that from Tuesday on, people can
call "111", a special telephone number in the country to acquire
knowledge of AIDS for consultancy.
</P>
<P>
Cohen noted the theme of this year's World AIDS Day -- "young
people -- a new force in the fight against AIDS."
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that young people aged from 10 to 20 years
account for 30 percent of the total population in underdeveloped
countries.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the deputy minister called upon the Angolan youths
to respect the status of AIDS patients and the HIV positive
people in both families and the society and their rights to work,
and to help them fight against the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Cohen quoted a document from the United Nations Program on
HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) as saying that there are now 33.4 million
people who have been infected with HIV/AIDS, and 70 percent of
them are living in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS document added that AIDS is killing people at the
rate of 11 per minute, or 16,000 per day.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) also said that so far in
1998, 2.5 million people have been killed by AIDS, and 83 percent
of the victims were in Africa.
</P>
<P>
December 1 was set as the World AIDS Day at the International
Conference on AIDS in London in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
