<HEADLINE> France to Join U.S. Mars Exploration Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- France will join the U.S. project
exploring the Mars by sending an orbiter to the red planet in
2005, said French Minister of National Education and Science
Research Claude Allegre on Monday.
</P>
<P>
France will spend 2.5 billion francs (420 million U.S. dollars)
in the program to cooperate with the United States in the
exploration, the daily Le Monde Tuesday quoted Allegre as saying.
</P>
<P>
France and the United States will sign a memorandum of
understanding on the sending by France of an orbiter with the
Ariane rocket to the Mars in 2005, in order to bring back to earth
soil samples from the planet.
</P>
<P>
An American landing machine and an American robot will be flown
on the orbiter to the Mars. The robot will collect the samples.
</P>
<P>
The head of the U.S. National Aviation and Space Agency (NASA),
Daniel Goldin, asked France to provide an Ariane-5 rocket in the
Martial exploration when he visited France in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
The French National Center of Space Study (CNES) agreed to the
U.S. request because it now has a budget for its 2000-2005 working
plan and beyond, said Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
The United States is spending 11 billion francs (1.8 billion
U.S.dollars) on the Mars exploration plan.
</P>
<P>
France joined the U.S.-Russian joined space exploration by
sending two astronauts to the ``Mir'' space station by U.S. space
aircraft in 1996 and 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
