<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Agriculture to Grow in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's entire agricultural
sector is estimated to grow by 3.2 percent this year with most
crops registering reduced yields because of the initial
uncertainty over the impact of the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe Tuesday said in its annual report
that maize output is estimated at 1.46 million tons this year, a
decrease of 19.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
This year's cotton crop is estimated at 300,000 tons, an
increase of 11.1 percent but prices are still below farmers'
expectations, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco, the country's biggest foreign currency earner, has
been low despite the generally better quality crop of 210 million
kilograms, a 7.7 percent increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
The importance of horticulture as a foreign currency earner
had been growing rapidly and 10,951 tons of cut flowers were
exported during the 1997/98 season, generating 50 million U.S.
Dollars. Exports of other horticultural produce realized 23
million Dollars, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
