<HEADLINE> Egypt, Sudan Discuss Cooperation in Judicial Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Justice
Farouk Seif el-Nasr held talks Tuesday with his Sudanese
counterpart Ali Osman Yassin on cooperation in the legal and
judicial areas.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the talks, the Sudanese official
said that Egypt has expressed readiness to extend assistance to
Sudan in training judicial personnel.
</P>
<P>
Yassin underlined Sudan's keenness on promoting cooperation
with Egypt in various domains.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Egypt and Sudan soured in 1995 after
Cairo accused Khartoum of masterminding an assassination attempt
against President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also blamed Sudan for harboring Islamic militants who
began a violent campaign in 1992 to topple Mubarak's secular
government and install a strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
A thaw in the bilateral ties seems to have set in in
recent years after the two neighbors expressed readiness to
improve their relations and exchanged visits by officials.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held earlier in the day, Yassin said that
his country is committed to the Arab anti-terrorism agreement,
which it has signed.
</P>
<P>
He voiced Sudan's willingness to cooperate with all other Arab
countries in fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries signed their first ever joint anti-terrorism
agreement last April, under which the signatories should exchange
information about terrorist acts and extradite terrorists.
</P>
<P>
The agreement opposes any possible attempts by the signatory
parties to organize, finance, commit or take part in terrorist
acts against any other party in any way.
</P>
<P>
Yassin arrived here during the weekend for the two-day 14th
session of the Arab Justice Ministers Council opening Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
