<HEADLINE> 76 Rwanda Genocide Suspects Freed: RNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-six genocide suspects
were released from Rilima Prison, south of capital Kigali, for
lack of enough evidence for charges or incomplete files, Rwanda
News Agency (RNA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Those freed are among the first of 10,000 genocide suspects
the current Rwandan government has decided to set free on similar
grounds.
</P>
<P>
For May this year, the local criminal court of Nyamata had
registered 138 detainees without files, but 62 of them were later
completed.
</P>
<P>
Rilima Prison hosts 7,604 inmates, 273 of whom are former
Rwandan government soldiers, charged with involvement in killing
more than 500,000 people in 1994 in the country.
</P>
<P>
Over 125,000 genocide suspects are currently detained in
Rwandan prisons and communal lock-ups, waiting for trial, RNA
said, in a special dispatch to Xinhua based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The recent decision by the government to release 10,000
suspects without complete files had raised temper among
organizations catering for genocide survivors who claim that they
have been betrayed, and that there is no fair justice.
</P>
<P>
However, Rwandan authorities have reassured them by saying
that the release is not definite since if enough evidence is
produced against them by their neighbors, they could be thrown
back into jail again and punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0030 </DOCNO>
