<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Tackle Trade Deficit With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will try its best to
deal with its trade deficit issue with Japan, a senior government
official said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus saw its imports from Japan this year stand at about 100
million Cyprus pounds (about 200 million U.S. dollars), but its
exports to Japan only around 500,000 pounds (about one million
dollars), said Minister of Commerce, Industry and Tourism Nicos
Rolandis after meeting with Japanese Ambassador to Cyprus Kazuo
Matsumoto.
</P>
<P>
Rolandis is expected to visit Japan next June, during which he
will discuss with Japanese officials trade issues, as well as more
Japanese investments in Cyprus' industrial, high technology and
service fields.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he would seek ways to attract more Japanese
tourists to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Rolandis also raised the issue of second-hand
Japanese cars exported to Cyprus and asked for clarifications as
to whether they are up to European Union (EU) standards.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, there has been a sharp increase in the
number of Japanese second-hand cars exported to Cyprus as they are
cheaper than others, especially than those from European countries.
</P>
<P>
Rolandis said that in the future all exports to Cyprus must be
of European standards.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU membership in July 1990 and started its
accession talks with the EU last March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
