<HEADLINE> Steps to Restore Confidence in Economy Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean National Chamber
of Commerce Tuesday urged the government to take immediate
measures to restore confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The chamber said in a statement released here that a repeat of
this year's negative developments will turn the country into a
haven for social and political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
It said the government must make public how it was funding its
involvement in the Democratic Republic of Congo and ensure that
the intervention does not severely impact on budgetary targets.
</P>
<P>
It urged the government to implement land reforms as agreed by
all stake-holders at the land donor conference in September.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, investigations into widespread corruption within
the national oil company should be stepped up and the findings
made public," the chamber said.
</P>
<P>
Stepping up efforts to recover millions of Dollars looted from
the War Victims Compensation Fund and the National Housing Fund
would also help rebuild business confidence, the business
organization said.
</P>
<P>
"All those who looted from the funds, including government
ministers, should be prosecuted," it said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the minister of finance and the governor of the
Reserve Bank should make regular statements to the nation on the
performance of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The government has already received similar demands from the
labor movement which has threatened to defy the presidential ban
of mass job stay-aways if negotiation between the government,
labor and private sector fail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
