<HEADLINE> Israeli Peace Activists Clash with Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Members of an Israeli peace
group Tuesday clashed with the police in the controversial Har
Homa construction area in east Jerusalem as they tried to halt a
bidding tour on the site.
</P>
<P>
The clashed took place as several Israeli contractors
interested in Har Homa building project toured the site in a
convoy of cars, reported the Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen Peace Now Movement members protesting against the
construction plan tried to approach the site but were stopped by
the police.
</P>
<P>
Three Peace Now members were then detained during their clashes
with the police.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government planned to build 6,500 houses for Jews
at Har Homa in the traditionally Arab east Jerusalem captured by
Israel from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
The move was regarded provocative by the Palestinians, who want
to establish an independent state in the future with east
Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
It was the Israeli decision to break ground at Har Homa for
Jewish settlement expansion in March 1997 that brought the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process to a 19-month deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Israeli National Infrastructure Ministry announced on Tuesday
that it has authorized the construction of 480 housing units in
the Jewish settlement of Kohav Yaacov, northwest of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In response, Palestinian Council Speaker Abu Ala Tuesday called
on all the Palestinians to join the struggle against Jewish
settlements. 
</P>
