<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A 15-member team of election
observers from African countries arrived in Nigerian capital
Abuja Monday to monitor the December 5 local government elections
in the most populous African country.
</P>
<P>
The team from the Association of African Election Authorities
(AAEA) and the International Foundation for Election System
(IFES) came to the west African country on the invitation of the
Nigerian government, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued in Abuja quoted K. Afri-Syan, Executive
Secretary of AAEA and Chairman of the Electoral Commission of
Ghana, as saying that the presence of the team during Saturday's
elections demonstrates the support of African election officials,
non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and the international
community for the elections in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"The AAEA/IFES mission is unlike most others in that the
participants have practical experience in the administration of
elections throughout the Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
The AAEA members of the team is mainly composed of election
experts from Kenya, Zimbabwe, Ghana, Liberia, Benin, Cameroon and
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the team would join IFES's long-term
monitors who have been in Nigeria since November 15 and the team
members would be deployed to different parts of the country to
monitor the elections.
</P>
<P>
The IFES will remain in the country until the conclusion of
the presidential election in February next year while AAEA will
return in February to join the IFES, according to the statement.
