<HEADLINE> Ugandan Minister Defends Military Presence in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Minister for Defense
Steven Kavuma reaffirmed Tuesday afternoon that his country's
military presence in the eastern part of the Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC) is to guarantee national security.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Kavuma said the Ugandan
troops are also there to prevent the occurence of genocide.
</P>
<P>
Uganda will pull out of DRC as soon as its security concerns
are properly addressed and it is assured that no genocide is to
occur there, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to a mutual understanding between the governments of
Uganda and Congo (k), Uganda began to send troops to eastern DRC
one year before the August 2 rebellion, he said.
</P>
<P>
Former Zairean leader Mobutu Sese Seko supported and trained
rebels who fought against the Ugandan government. That is why
Uganda hoped that DRC President Laurent Kabila can solve the
border security issue when he, with the help of Uganda and
Rwanda, came to power in May 1997, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
He also refuted recent reports that the Ugandan army recruited
street children, saying the report is laughable and explained
that it is against Uganda's policy to recruit soldiers against
their will.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the minister asserted, Uganda has enough
mature soldiers, so it does not need to use street children who
do not have much fighting capacity.
</P>
<P>
When asked if they will fight Zimbabwean troops in DRC, he
said: "We have no intention to fight against our brothers in
Zimbabwe, but we will defend if attacked."
</P>
<P>
"We have the will, means, capacity to defend Uganda from
aggression. If anyone makes the mistake of attacking us, we will
deal with them," the Ugandan minister said.
</P>
<P>
Kavuma also revealed that infrastructure in northern Uganda is
being improved and the army is being equipped for the purpose of
dealing with the rebels of the Lord's Resistance Army.
</P>
<P>
Since the Tutsi rebellion in early August, Kabila has accused
Uganda of fomenting and backing the rebels who fought to topple
his government and of invading his country, a charge Kampala
immediately denied.
</P>
<P>
Kabila deems Uganda and Rwanda as aggressors and asks them to
leave his country while the latter demand all foreign troops,
including the allied forces who are fighting alongside Kabila's
army, to withdraw from of the country at the same time because
the DRC crisis is an internal issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
