<HEADLINE> AL Renews Call for Israeli Withdrawal From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Amid mounting tensions in south
Lebanon, Arab League Tuesday renewed its call for an unconditional
Israeli withdrawal as a way to realize peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made here by the organization's Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid in a meeting with outgoing Lebanese
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
His call came as Israeli military brass and cabinet members are
threatening to strike Lebanon's infrastructures in retaliation for
the recent killings of seven Israeli soldiers by resistance
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the roadside bomb attacks. The latest
casualties brought the death toll of Israeli soldiers in south
Lebanon to 23 since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said the situation in south Lebanon is very dangerous,
and called Israel's self-styled security zone there "a zone
without security."
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out the border strip in 1985 after two invasions,
with the claimed aim of protecting its north from cross-border
attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance spearheaded by Hezbollah has
been fighting against Israeli forces and its Lebanese allies.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said that Israel's unconditional withdrawal from
Lebanon, as called for by the international community, is urgently
needed.
</P>
<P>
Israel offered in April to withdraw from south Lebanon on
condition that Lebanon makes arrangements to guarantee the
security Israel's north territory.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the "conditional" proposal, demanding that
Israel leave the country without any preconditions, as stipulated
in the U.N. Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Meguid arrived here Monday night on a personal visit to launch
his book "the Age of Defeat and Victory" published by a Lebanese
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
