<HEADLINE> Iraqi Minister Terms Arab Meeting Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Justice Minister Shabib
al-Maliki Tuesday termed as "successful" the 14th session of the
Arab Justice Ministers Council.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before leaving here for Baghdad,
al-Maliki said the outcome of the session reflected Arab
countries' keenness on maintaining cooperation in the legal and
judicial fields.
</P>
<P>
The Arab council, which ended its two-day annual session
Monday, discussed the drafting of an agreement for fighting
organized crimes across the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
As a major achievement of the session, the participating
countries agreed to set up a committee for promoting the
implementation of an Arab anti-terrorism agreement, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries which have not signed the agreement were
urged to do so as soon as possible, al-Maliki added.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached last April at a joint meeting of the
councils of Arab justice ministers and interior ministers.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the signatories are required to exchange
information about terrorist activities and extradite terrorists.
</P>
<P>
The agreement opposes any possible attempts of the signatory
parties to organize, finance, commit or take part in terrorist
acts against any other party in any way.
</P>
<P>
Al-Maliki, who arrived here on Saturday for the meeting, said
that during his stay in Cairo, he also discussed with his Egyptian
counterpart Farouk Seif al-Nasr issues related to an agreement on
bilateral cooperation in the judicial field. 
</P>
