<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan's Oil Output Sets Record This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 1 (Xinhua) - Turkmenistan's oil output in the
year is expected to exceed five million tones, breaking a record
over the past seven years, the Ministry for Oil and Gas Industry
and Mineral Resources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, oil output of
Turkmenneft's state oil company in January-November 1998 averaged
about 17,500 tons each day. Before the end of the year the overall
output will be 5.5 million tones.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the production volumes of foreign
companies, a total of 6,5 million tons of oil will be produced on
Turkmen territory this year, the Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkmen oil industry is going through a revival, said the
Ministry. The production volume in the past two years has been
rising by about 20 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The start of this decade marked a crisis for Turkmenistan's oil
sector. Production volumes fell to a little more than four million
tons each year.
</P>
<P>
In opinion of Deputy Prime Minister Batyr Sardzhayev, in charge of
the oil and gas sector, the country's oil output will grow to 50
million tons in 2010.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan's oil reserves, including the Caspian offshore
fields, are estimated at 12 billion tons, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
