<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annual AIDS Infections in EU Around 30,000, Says EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- European epidemiologists
estimate the annual number of new AIDS infections within the
European Union (EU) to be around 30,000, said European
Commissioner Padraig Flynn on the occasion of World AIDS Day,
December 1.
</P>
<P>
This figure, he said, has not fallen over the last two years,
indicating that efforts at prevention is taking time.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 500,000 people in the European Union have
the HIV virus, Flynn said. Since the epidemic began, nearly
200,000 cases of AIDS have been declared within the Union, 60
percent of whom are known to have died.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the incidence of AIDS has steadily declined in all
the EU member states thanks to the availability of new
anti-retroviral treatment which prevent or delay the onset of the
disease among the HIV-positive, he said.
</P>
<P>
When recalling the EU's commitment to combat AIDS, Flynn said
"we must continue our efforts unremittingly, coordinating
activities under different policies and bringing together all the
players involved: the health professionals, patients'
associations, the authorities, and non-governmental and
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU' executive body, has provided
so far this year financial support totaling 10 million European
currency units (about 11 million US dollars) to some 40 projects
or European networks under a five-year program for prevention of
AIDS and other communicable diseases, according to Flynn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
