<HEADLINE> U.S. to Release Pinochet-related Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday it will declassify and make public documents relating to
human rights abuses during the rule of former Chilean dictator
Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
"The administration is conducting a review of documents in its
possession that may shed light on human rights abuses during the
Pinochet era," said State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told a news briefing that "We will declassify and make
public as much information as possible consistent" with U.S. laws
and law enforcement needs.
</P>
<P>
Human rights groups have been pressing the United States to
take a stand on the case of Pinochet who was arrested in London on
October 16 following a request from a Spanish judge who wants him
to face charges of murder, torture and genocide.
</P>
<P>
They have also called for the United States to release
documents pertaining to the period when the former leader ruled
Chile.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration still did not have an opinion on the
merits of the case, said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman stressed that the United States has a
record of strongly condemning abuses that occurred during
Pinochet's rule.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also reiterated that the views of a democratic country
like Chile in this case must be given "respect." Chile is trying
to persuade Britain not to extradite Pinochet to Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
