<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Announces Its measures to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Marking the 11th World AIDS
Day here Tuesday, U.S. President Bill Clinton announced a range of
measures to cut the spread of AIDS and slow the growing world
population of children orphaned by the disease.
</P>
<P>
The White House announced that it would devote 10 million U.S.
Dollars to help orphans stay in school, assisting them with food
and job-training, and prepare people in their communities to
become foster parents.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. estimates, nearly 8 million children have
been orphaned by AIDS and at least 1 million children are infected
with the virus. 90 percent of them are now living in southern
African countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Agency for International Development projects that as
many as 40 million children worldwide will become orphans by 2010
as AIDS claims their parents. Sandra Thurman, the White House AIDS
policy adviser, will lead a U.S. delegation to southern Africa to
evaluate the situation there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. National Institutes of Health will create
an international network to share information about research on
how to control the spread of HIV among adults and from mothers
to newborns.
</P>
<P>
At home, NIH plans to spend an added 47 million U.S. Dollars
on efforts to develop AIDS vaccines, thus bring NIH's total
investment on such research to 200 million U.S. Dollars. Vice
President Al Gore announced 200 million U.S. Dollars for housing
assistance for AIDS patients and their families. Besides these
efforts, U.S. Congress has approved funding increases for a
range of HIV/AIDS programs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
