<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Goes Up 0.3 Pct in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Spurred by strong economic
growth and low interest rates, the U.S. construction spending
edged a moderate 0.3 percent in October, the fifth consecutive
increase, the Commerce Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Spending advanced to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 665.8
billion U.S. dollars in the month, following an identical 0.3
percent growth in September, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction increased 0.8 percent to a seasonally
adjusted rate of 306.8 billion dollars, with gains in both
single-family and apartment construction.
</P>
<P>
Commercial construction rose 0.9 percent to a rate of 168.4
billion dollars. Increases in office and shopping-center
construction offset declines in industrial structures and hotels.
Government construction spending decreased 1.5 percent to a rate
of 147.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
