<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Iraq's Oil Industry in Tatters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIRKUK, NORTHERN IRAQ, December 2 (Xinhua) -- With more than
1,000 oil wells and high yield of crude, Kirkuk, some 300
kilometers north of capital Baghdad, once earned its name of a
city "floating on the sea of oil."
</P>
<P>
But it no longer is. Past glories of the important oil city are
nowhere to be found. What often meet the eye are dilapidated
installations, poorly-maintained wells and rusty pipelines.
</P>
<P>
Eight years ago as the Gulf War was waged to end Iraqi
occupation of neighboring Kuwait, the city and its oil fields were
the main targets of air strikes of the U.S.-led allied forces.
Most of the facilities fell victim to the showers of bombs in the
"Desert Storm," said Ashur Talal, general manager of Kirkuk-based
Iraq North Oil Company.
</P>
<P>
After the war ended, Kirkuk's suffering was prolonged by the
ensuing U.N. sanctions, which became eight years old earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
Talal told Xinhua that the lack of spare parts is the major
problem facing the country and his company, and many oil wells had
to be shut for this reason.
</P>
<P>
"we need at least 100 million U.S. dollars to innovate our
facilities, but many of our contracts signed with foreign
companies have not been approved by the U.N. Sanctions Committee,"
he complained.
</P>
<P>
A blanket trade embargo was slapped on Iraq following its
invasion of Kuwait, but the U.N. made an exception by allowing
Baghdad to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six
months since December 1996 to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling was raised to 5.2 billion dollars in the fourth
phase, which expired on December 25, and a fifth phase has been
extended.
</P>
<P>
But the ruined oil installations made Iraq virtually impossible
to produce that much. In the fourth phase, the country had to
settle for only 3.3 billion dollars in oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council decided in June to allow Iraq to
import 300 million dollars worth of direly-needed spare parts to
revamp its oil installations.
</P>
<P>
But so far, only a batch of spare parts have arrived. And the
managers of oil refineries complained that they could not find
anything useful for them in the shipments because the spare parts
were only for oil production, not refining.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's daily oil output has dwindled to today's 2.6 million
barrels from 3.2 million prior to the sanctions, while its daily
exports dropped to 1.7 million barrels from 2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
Iraq exports its crude largely through two pipelines linking
Kirkuk and Turkey, which were reopened in December 1996 after six
years of suspension under the sanctions. But their transfer
capacity has sharply declined for lack of spare parts and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions not only damaged Iraq's oil production and
exports, but also weakened its refining capacity. Such vicious
circle would surely destroy Iraq's economic lifeline - oil
industry," Talal said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Hails Formation of New Business Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region Tung Chee Hwa Wednesday
reaffirmed Hong Kong's commitment to free market and trade
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration ceremony of Hong Kong, China
Business Council, a new affiliate of the International Chamber of
Commerce (ICC), Tung said: "As a staunch supporter of free market
and free trade, Hong Kong fully shares the Chamber's objective to
promote market economy and the free flow of trade in goods and
services in the world economy."
</P>
<P>
ICC, the world business organization with members in over 130
countries, has for many years counted companies and associations
in Hong Kong as direct members. The launch of the Hong Kong, China
Business Council will give the Hong Kong business community a
voice in global trade policy debate.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive said the establishment of the business
council would promote Hong Kong's business interest overseas and
foster business relations with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The newly formed Council has 46 members, including companies,
associations and chambers of commerce in Hong Kong. 
</P>
