<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arabian mining company, known as "Maadin,"
was granted a license to prospect for precious metals in the Al
Duweihi region, southeast of Zolm which falls within the Mecca
emirate (western Saudi Arabia), reported the Arab daily Al Hayat
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The prospective gold ore in the area is estimated at 14,000
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's exports of shoes and leather goods to the six
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states amounted to 25 million
Egyptian pounds (7.35 million U.S. dollars), of which
over 65 percent is consumed by Saudi Arabia alone.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, Egypt's exports of shoes and leather goods to the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) stood at 700,000 pounds (206,000
dollars) a year, a modest figure in terms of Egypt's potential
production and exports.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab Bank for Economic Development in Africa has
decided to extend three soft loans of 26.7 million U.S. dollars to
finance development projects in Botswana, Benin and Ghana, the
Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SALALAH -- With the inauguration of Raysut port here on
Tuesday, Oman added a new container transfer hub to the
Asian-European maritime route which has been booming over the past
years.
</P>
<P>
The port will mainly serve as a transit trade hub between the Gulf
region and Asian, European and African countries, reported the
Arab daily Al Hayat on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The construction costs of the first phase of the port amounted
to about 135 million U.S. dollars, borne by the Omani
government. And the second phase will be financed by private
sectors, covering the purchase of necessary equipment and
appliances at a cost of 120 million to 140 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of the four-dock port stands at some 2 million
containers a year in 1999 and will rise to 15 million a year after
construction completion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
