<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russia Needs IMF Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia wants to reach an
agreement with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to receive
10.3 billion U.S. dollars in new credit, Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Federation Council (the upper chamber), Primakov
said, "We are interested in reaching an agreement with the IMF
since otherwise we cannot reschedule our debts at the Paris Club,
cannot receive new credits, including the united loan from Japan
worth 800 million dollars."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister Wednesday met with the IMF Managing Director
Michel Camdessus, who arrived here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the talks, Primakov said relations with the IMF are of great
importance and have good prospects for development.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said Camdessus knows the situation in Russia very well
and has shown understanding for state participation during the
existing economic processes.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF head cautioned against state participation
that may go beyond certain boundaries and thwart the country's
progress to the market economy, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Camdessus said Primakov's practical attitude toward
the economy has paved the way for Russia's further cooperation
with the IMF.
</P>
<P>
According to Camdessus, during his talk with the prime
minister, the two sides did not discuss fiscal issues in
detail. He warned that the country needs to exercise strict budget
discipline and tight fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
He said steps taken by the Russian government are correct and
the IMF expects more details on this work before another IMF
mission arrives in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The IMF will send a mission to Russia next January to discuss
further cooperation with the country, Camdessus said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
