<HEADLINE> Blair's New Bid to Break Peace Deadlock in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair is to make a visit to Northern Ireland on Wednesday
afternoon to seek a breakthrough in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Blair's surprise trip, the second within two weeks, has
hightened speculation that an announcement of substantial progress
is imminent.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister is anxious to resolve the impasse in
Northern Ireland's politics, brought about by arguments over the
balance of new bodies established in the Northern Ireland peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern may join Blair for the latest
round of top-level talks in Belfast, according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
In an historic speech to both house of the Irish Parliament
last week, Blair appealed to both sides in Northern Ireland to
reach consensus.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It is time now I believe for all the parties to live
up to all their commitment, time for north-south bodies to be set
up, time to set up the institutions for a new government, time for
the gun to be taken out of politics once and for all.
</P>
<P>
"I am not asking anyone to surrender, I am asking everyone to
declare the victory of peace."
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's Deputy First Minister Seamus Mallon warned
the entire peace process would collapse unless a deal was struck
on the composition of the new institutions within days.
</P>
<P>
That deadline, like a number of others recently, has passed
without progress.
</P>
<P>
But Mallon said on Wednesday he was "still confident that
before the end of the week we will have a resolution to this
matter".
</P>
<P>
The deputy first minister was speaking during talks with First
Minister David Trimble, who talked to Blair on Tuesday by
telephone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
