<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Chairman Meets Japanese Youth Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua)-- Chairman Li Peng of the
Standing Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress met
with a Japanese youth delegation here today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, composed of members of the House of
Representatives and delegates from about 30 youth societies, is
here to mark the 20th anniversary of the China-Japan Peace and
Friendship Treaty, at the invitation of the All-China Youth
Federation.
</P>
<P>
Li said the celebration to mark the occasion, and further
exploration of ways to expand and deepen contacts between young
people of the two countries, will play an active role in
stimulating bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The normalization of relations between China and Japan,
together with the signing of the peace and friendship treaty,
opened up a new era in bilateral relations, Li said. President
Jiang Zemin's recent state visit to Japan, an important event in
bilateral ties at this trans-century juncture, is significant for
the development of long-term friendly cooperation oriented to the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Li recalled that when he was visiting Japan in 1989, Okazaki
Kaheita, a long-time friend of China, accompanied him on his visit
to Okayama despite his venerable age, and today his son is a
member of the delegation. This shows that friendship between the
two countries is a matter concerning to all generations, Li said.
</P>
<P>
In developing bilateral relations, Li pointed out, there are
three basic points to be taken into consideration. First, a
correct attitude towards history should be adopted; second, broad
communication should be carried out; and third, the hopes for
future bilateral relations lie in the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
At this juncture of inheriting the past and ushering in the
future, the youth of both countries shoulder important
responsibilities for passing on this friendship, he
said. Therefore, he expressed the hope that young parliament
members of both countries will increase their contact, and the
All-China Youth Federation will expand relations with Japanese
youth societies to contribute to lasting friendship between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Azuma Syozo, deputy secretary-general of Japan's Liberal Party
and also a member of the House of Representatives, said the
delegates share the common goal of developing long-term
Japan-China friendship, and although they have different
professions and are from diverse backgrounds, they are all
determined to further friendship programs and contribute to better
bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
