<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Form Independent Anti-Fraud Investigation Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
form an independent investigation office to strengthen its
anti-fraud task force, the European Commission said here Wednesday
after adopting a proposal for a regulation to create such a body.
</P>
<P>
The office will be responsible solely for investigations on
suspected fraud or corruption and will be wholly independent of
the commission, the EU's executive agency.
</P>
<P>
The main task of the office is to carry out enquiries both
externally in the EU member states and internally inside all
institutions of the European Union, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
The move is in line with the commission's commitment to
protect the European taxpayers' money.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the EU is of firm conviction that this
proposal will form a good basis for discussion between the
institutions on how to further strengthen the fight against fraud
and corruption harmful to the European taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
Under European Union treaties, the commission has the right of
initiative in respect of legislation, the coordination of anti-fraud
activities with the member states and the launching of both internal
and external investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Batty Move on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- England midfielder David Batty
has returned to train with Newcastle after his prospective return
to Leeds was put on hold.
</P>
<P>
The clubs are as much as two million pounds apart in their
valuation of the player, who turns 30 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Leeds have already made a bid of around four million but
Newcastle apparently want as much as six million, although this
valuation may be designed to simply squeeze a little more cash
out of Leeds.
</P>
<P>
It is thought that should they go up their offer to 4.5
million it would clinch a deal.
</P>
<P>
Batty's personal terms are apparently a formality and he is
said to be prepared to waive an 800,000 pounds payment to secure
his return to West Yorkshire, where he still lives with his
family.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle chairman Freddy Shepherd, who never wanted to sell
the player in the first place, is refusing to let him go at a
knock-down price.
</P>
<P>
"Without revealing how much we think he is worth, I would say
4 million is nowhere near enough," he said.
</P>
<P>
Batty says he has no quarrel with his current club, although
he submitted a transfer request to Newcastle manager Ruud Gullit
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He has never made any secret of the fact that he did not want
to leave Leeds back in 1994 when he was sold to Blackburn.
</P>
<P>
Even though other clubs are interested, it is unlikely that he
would go anywhere but Elland Road.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle's insistence that Leeds manager David O'Leary pay
more for the player could hold things up, but it would be a
surprise if the move does not go through at some stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Initiates Fund Guaranteeing Small-Enterprise Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing municipal authorities
today established a special 100-million-yuan fund (about 12
million U.S. dollars) for guaranteeing the financing of small
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Small and medium-sized businesses have been playing an ever
greater role in the economic life of the city in recent years,
local officials said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the output value of these enterprises
accounted for 60 percent of Beijing's total in 1997. In addition,
they provided 75 percent of the city's job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
However, because of their relatively small size and limited
capital, they often find it difficult to secure bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The new fund, set up by the local government and two investment
companies, will guarantee one billion yuan in loans for these
enterprises, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Any promising enterprise which complies with the state's
industrial development policy and has good market prospects
can obtain support from this fund.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
