<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Rejects Philippines' Claim on Sabah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Sabah State
Chief Minister Bernard Dompok Wednesday brushed aside the
Philippines' claim on Sabah, saying the issue was resolved a long
time ago.
</P>
<P>
The people of Sabah have expressed their loyalty to Malaysia,
which means further discussion on this issue is not necessary,
Dompok told reporters after the weekly state cabinet meeting in
Kota Kinabalu, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
Two Philippine newspapers reported recently that the Philippine
government has not given up its claim on Sabah, according to
Malaysia's state news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Bernama said the Manila Bulletin and the Philippine Daily
Inquirer quoted Philippine presidential spokesman Fernado Barican
as saying that the claim had only been frozen under Fidel Ramos'
administration and it had not been dropped.
</P>
<P>
Bernama quoted Dompok as saying that, "We don't recognize
it. It is a closed file. It is water under the bridge. It is gone."
</P>
<P>
Hishammudin Tun Hussein, acting youth chief of Malaysia's
ruling party United Malays National Organization (UMNO), said
earlier that the Philippines' claim on Sabah was a clear
infringement on Malaysia's sovereign integrity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
