<HEADLINE> U.S. Coca-Cola to Increase Market Share in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Coca-Cola Group is
confident of doubling its business in south Africa by 2003,
Wednesday's Business Day daily quoted a senior official of the
group as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an international seminar on African trade and
investment in Cape Town, Don Knauss, one of presidents of the
Coca-Cola Group responsible for southern Africa, said that of the
nearly 200 countries where Coca-Cola runs business, South Africa
is its 10th largest market.
</P>
<P>
"Still, we believe we're just getting started. In this
country, carbonated soft drinks account for only five percent of
commercial beverage consumption... only one out of 20 drinks,"
Knauss said.
</P>
<P>
He said his group is planning to invest 750 million Rand
(about 125 million U.S. Dollars) to promote the Coca-Cola
business in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Starting in South Africa next year, we are planning to launch
a 'people's Coke', an affordable, single serve 350 returnable
bottle at 1.5 Rand (one U.S. Dollar equals to about six Rand)...
a price we want to maintain for several years," Knauss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
