<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Marks 1st Anniversary of Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh observed the first
anniversary of the signing of the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT)
peace agreement between the government and the tribal rebels on
Wednesday with mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Awami League (AL) held various activities to
celebrate the occasion, tribal leaders voiced dissatisfaction over
the slow implementation of the accord, while the opposition is
still opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
The AL held a discussion here hailing the accord, which the
government signed on December 2, 1997 with the Parbattaya
Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS), the political wing of the
pro-independence armed rebels.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party also organized processions and rallies at the
hill district headquarters on Wednesday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While the accord has been hailed by many as an "historic
event," which ended over two decades of armed conflict in the
country's three southeastern hill districts, it has also aroused
mixed reactions among Bangladeshi people, particularly people from
different strata in the hill districts with regard to what the
peace accord has actually brought about in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The PCJSS organized rallies to voice its dissatisfaction over
the delay in implementing the accord.
</P>
<P>
"It is not true that the peace accord is not being implemented,
but the progress is very slow," said Shantu Larma,
chairman-designate of the CHT regional council to be established
under the accord, and president of the PCJSS.
</P>
<P>
"A particular quarter in the government is involved in...
delaying implementation of the peace accord," he said, adding: "We
will continue non-violent means to press home our demand."
</P>
<P>
"The implementation process of the accord has slowed down. No
significant progress was visible from the government side,"
another PCJSS leader said, urging the government to expedite the
implementation.
</P>
<P>
"People are breathing in a peaceful atmosphere. Tribal refugees
have come back. Their rehabilitation has started. Everywhere there
is a symbol of solidarity. It's the main achievement of the
agreement," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The major opposition the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP),
however, has opposed the CHT peace accord from the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Tuesday to mark the anniversary of the
peace deal, BNP General Secretary Mannan Bhuiyan said government
leaders would have to "stand public trial" for signing the
"anti-state" accord with the tribals.
</P>
<P>
"December 2 is a black day as the government, on this day in
1997, signed such an accord as it runs counter to the Constitution
as well as country's sovereignty and integrity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Awami League-dominated parliament passed three bills in May
this year giving legal effect to the accord, but the full
implementation of the deal remains an uphill task for the
government, considering the present political confrontation
between the ruling party and the opposition, and the disputes
between the government and the PCJSS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
