<HEADLINE> Senior CPC Leader Meets Cameroun Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, a member of the
Political Bureau Standing Committee of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) Central Committee, said today that the CPC will
further strengthen friendship and cooperation with the Cameroun
People's Democratic Rally (CPDR) on the basis of the four
principles guiding party relations.
</P>
<P>
The two parties will learn from each other and engage in joint
efforts to promote both party and national relations, said Li. He
made the comments in an afternoon meeting here this afternoon with
a CPDR delegation led by General Secretary Joseph Charles Doumba.
</P>
<P>
Li, who also serves as chairman of the National People's
Congress Standing Committee, noted that the CPC is delighted with
achievements the people of Cameroun have made under the leadership
of President Paul Biya. He also pointed to the enduring good
relations between the CPC and CPDR.
</P>
<P>
The NPC leader noted Cameroun's vast resources and great
development potential. He noted that elections in the country have
laid a solid foundation for stability and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed to the smooth development of relations between the
two countries over the past few years and expressed great
appreciation for the warm reception he received during last year's
visit to Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
The delegation's visit to China will undoubtedly promote the
further development of relations between the two parties and the
two countries, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the desirable progress in bilateral cooperation
in various fields, including the political, economic and cultural
arenas, to joint efforts and expressed China's appreciation for
the "one China" stand of the Cameroun government.
</P>
<P>
Doumba said President Biya, the government and ruling party
attach great importance to relations with China, and will continue
to extend great efforts to the development of relations between
all nation's on the African continent and China.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders briefed each other on the political and
economic situations in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
Dai Bingguo, director of the CPC Central Committee's
International Department, held talks with the delegation on
November 30. The delegation is visiting China at the invitation of
the CPC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
