<HEADLINE> China Develops Alternative Fuel Vehicles (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
coordinating efforts to accelerate the development and use of
electric and alternative fuel motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Deng Nan, vice-minister of Science and Technology, said today
that the government attaches great importance and has achieved
initial results in developing automobiles which burn clean fuel.
</P>
<P>
"Developing environmentally friendly motor vehicle technology
in line with China's resources is highly significant for ensuring
the sustainable development of the nation's automobile
manufacturing industry," according to Deng.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks at today's opening of the Second Beijing
International Seminar and Exhibition on Electric Vehicles and
Alternative Fuel Vehicles today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 13.9 million motor vehicles were sold in China
during 1997, including passenger vehicles, trucks, motorcycles and
tractors. This year's output of passenger vehicles and trucks is
expected to surpass 1.6 million units.
</P>
<P>
China has relatively limited oil reserves, but vast natural gas
resources and the nation has been a net importer of petroleum
products since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The five-day seminar and exhibition is sponsored by the
Ministry of Science and Technology, the State Administration of
Machinery Industry, China National Petroleum Corporation. and
China Petrochemical Corporation. Some 1,000 representatives from
the Chinese Government, the UNDP, foreign embassies in China, and
Chinese and foreign motor vehicle manufacturers and oil companies
are attending the seminar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Alternative Fuel Vehicles (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoyu, deputy director-general of the State
Administration of Machinery Industry, said that China considers
the development of electric and alternative fuel vehicles as an
important measure for dealing with problems related to air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
China had over 6,000 vehicles using gas as its fuel and over 70
gas refueling depots in 66 percent of the nation's provinces by
January this year.
</P>
<P>
The government has listed the development and commercialization
of electric vehicles as key national scientific and technological
programs. China has completed studies of various international
technological standards for electric vehicles and in turn
formulated related national standards. In addition, an electric
vehicle research and demonstration zone has been established in
Nan'ao, south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The government has also formed a coordination panel of experts
from the scientific and business sectors to develop electric and
alternative fuel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
China has also signed an agreement with an Italian design firm
to jointly develop concepts for electric vehicles and has
established joint projects with the United States, Japan and
Australia to develop alternative fuel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xinfang, deputy director-general of the State
Administration of Environmental Protection, said that clear fuel
technology should initially be applied to bus and taxi fleets in
major cities.
</P>
<P>
China has listed nine cities as "National Compressed Natural
and liquefied Petroleum Gas Vehicle Application and
Demonstration Cities."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
