<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Names New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's veteran politician
Salim Hoss was named Wednesday by President Emile Lahoud as the
next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The nomination came after Lahoud completed a two-day mandatory
consulations with the Parliament, in which 95 members in the
128-seat parliament voted to recommend Hoss.
</P>
<P>
Hoss, 69, a Doctor of Economics, has held the premiership on
three previous occasions. He was widely respected in Lebanon's
fractious politics for his reputation as an honest lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
Ever since he became a parliament member in 1992, Hoss has been
a prime critic of outgoing Prime Minister Rafik Hariri's economic
and social policies. His criticism has been characterized as
"constructive."
</P>
<P>
Like every prime minister under Lebanon's power-sharing
arrangement, Hoss is a Sunni Muslim. According to the arrangement,
the president is a Maronite Catholic and the Parliament speaker is
a Shiite Muslim.
</P>
<P>
After being sworn-in on November 24, Lahoud had asked Hariri to form
a new government. But the latter rejected his request.
</P>
<P>
The billionaire construction tycoon Hariri, who took office six
years ago, launched a multibillion dollar reconstruction drive to
rebuild Lebanon from the devastation of the 1975-90 civil war.
</P>
<P>
But during his six-year tenure, the country sank deep into debt
and ordinary Lebanese complained that the benefits of the
reconstruction did not filter down to them.
</P>
<P>
Press reports predicted the new cabinet, which will not exceed
16 ministers, will be announced at the weekend. Economic
development and government reform will be the major challenges of
the new government, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
