<HEADLINE> ... general elections. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Gesher decided last Wednesday to rejoin the government
and allow Levy to take the portfolio of national infrastrucutre.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who resigned as foreign minister in January over the
state budget issue and the lack of progress in the peace process,
has won certain concessions from Netanyahu for rejoining the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Besides taking the portfolio of a key ministry in the
coalition, Levy will be guaranteed the number-two spot on the
Likud list in the next Knesset's (parliament) elections, and he
will also join Netanyahu's inner "kitchen cabinet" and take part in
the final-status talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 400 to 500 Gesher members will be registered as
Likud Central Committee members and the state budget will provide
funding for the social concerns that prompted Levy's resignation
from the government in January.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has some trouble within his coalition because the
National Religous party (NRP) openly rejected the Wye peace
accord signed last month in Washington with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Two ministers of the NRP voted against the accord while
several NRP Knesset members threatened to join the oppostion in
the Knesset to bring the government down. Without Gesher, the
coalition only has 61 seats in the 120-member Kennset.
</P>
<P>
Some Likud members have voiced their objection to Levy's return
and the promise that so much Gesher members will be allowed to join
the Likud's Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Levy's brother, Maxim Levy, a Knesset
member, is also opposed to Geshe's merger with the Likud.
</P>
<P>
He said he has nothing against David Levy entering the
government again and picking up a minister portfolio as he
likes, but the merging with the Likud is something else and
Gesher should maintain its independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
