<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Backs Transition With 4 New Decrees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
signed four new decrees into law to give further legal backing to
the on-going transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports Wednesday, the new laws were signed
by Nigerian military leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the office of the Attorney General of the
Federation and the Minister of Justice said the new laws include
the Transition to Civil Rule (Political Program) Decree 1998,
which spells out the transition program.
</P>
<P>
Another is the Local Government (Basic Constitutional and
Transitional Provisions) Decree 1998, which provides the conduct
of local government elections and relevant offenses and penalties
as well as dispute resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The third decree is the Political Parties (Registration and
Activities) Decree 1998 and the fourth the Independent National
Electoral Commission (Amendment) Decree 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the transition to civil rule program announced by
Abubakar, the military government will hand over to an elected
civilian government on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The first election under the transition program, the election
of local government councils would start Saturday, December 5.
</P>
