<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Official Accuses U.S. of Using DU in Gulf War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Health Undersecretary
Shawqi Sabri said Wednesday the use of depleted uranium (DU) by
the U.S. and Britain during the Gulf War constituted a direct and
serious peril to the public health of Iraq because of the lethal
effects of this weapon.
</P>
<P>
Sabri was speaking at the opening session of an international
symposium on the use of depleted uranium (DU) and its impact on
man and environment in Iraq which was held in Baghdad. He added
that the use of DU has caused sever pollution to the environment
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A British veteran Ray Bristow who worked in a field hospital
in Saudi Arabia during the Gulf War, told Xinhua that he has been
suffering from a unnamed disease which is commonly referred to as
Gulf War syndrome.
</P>
<P>
Bristow said he suffers from pain in the joints and muscles,
extreme fatigue, frequency in passing water, all sorts of problems
with the bowel as well as depression and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
He said he has been tested positive in Canada, and tests
showed that he was exposed to UD poison over 100 times higher
than normal level.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Muthana Qasab, head of Adnan Hospital in Baghdad, told
Xinhua that since the Gulf War, his hospital has received many
patients who have suffered strange diseases he never come acoss
before.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium gathers together more than 200 experts
and specialists from the U.S., Britain, Canada, Germany, Jordan,
Tunisia and Iraq, as well as U.S. and British veterans who
participated in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, other national and
regional leaders of the Arab Socialist Baath Party, Iraqi Health
Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak and several Iraqi ministers attended
the opening session of the symposium.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, outside of the five-star Rasheed
Hotel where the symposium is being held, an angry crowd of more
than 100 people attending a mass funeral procession of 38 children
were shouting anti-U.S. slogans.
</P>
<P>
The funeral procession was sponsored by the Iraqi Association
for Children Support. Head of the organization Sultan al-Shawi
said these children died as a result of severe shortage of
food and medicine caused by the unjust embargo.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed crippling economic sanctions on Iraq
following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, which touched off the Gulf
War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
