<HEADLINE> Nigeria Plans Laws on Environmental Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government would
soon promulgate some laws aimed at providing an avenue for
victims of environmental damages to seek redress, a senior
environmental official has said.
</P>
<P>
R.O. Adewoye, the Director General of the Federal Environment
Protection Agency (FEPA) made the disclosure at a recent
international seminar on petroleum industry and environment in
Abuja, the Nigerian capital, according to Wednesday's Daily Times
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The official said the laws of response, compensation and
liability for environmental damage are coming on the heels of
draft national guidelines for solid waste management, water and
air quality, registration of green technology and environmental
management system being prepared by the FEPA.
</P>
<P>
He said the new laws would reduce further degradation of the
environment and provide a way of insulating the environment as an
issue from politics and ethnic struggles.
</P>
<P>
Environment pollutions in oil-producing areas have always been
a source of social unrest in Nigeria, which depends on oil export
for more than 90 percent of its hard currency incomes.
</P>
<P>
Aggrieved victims in the oil-producing communities have
repeatedly resorted to hostage taking and other violent means to
seek justice for oil companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
