<HEADLINE> Egyptian Newspaper Blames US for Iraqi Standoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- In a rare move, an official
Egyptian newspaper Wednesday accused the United States of
inventing excuses for keeping intact economic sanctions on Iraq
for its own interests.
</P>
<P>
Once the Iraqis have "a hope that their ordeal would come to an
end, the U.S. hurries to shatter the hope and fabricates fresh
pretexts to tighten the noose around them," the Egyptian Gazette
said in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
The current standoff, triggered by UNSCOM chief Richard
Butler's demand for more documents of Iraq's weapons programs, has
demonstrated the U.S. approach to the Iraqi crisis, the
English-language paper said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the trade embargo on Iraq
after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, which can not be lifted until
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) led by Butler certifies that
Iraq has destroyed the weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The paper maintains that the U.S. is attempting to "add fuel to
the flames and keep the Gulf volatile" for "more money to flow
into its coffers."
</P>
<P>
It cited the recent effort of U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen to tout the establishment of a U.S.-made sophisticated
missile system to the Gulf Arabs.
</P>
<P>
"Not unrelated is the eagerness of Washington to keep presence
in the region" to secure its interests, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It expressed sympathy for the "hapless Iraqis who continue to
pay dearly" for the U.S. drama which the paper said is "no longer
exciting, let alone humane."
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a close ally of Washington, receives over 2 billion
U.S. dollars in economic and military aid from the U.S. every
year. Its official newspapers usually keep mute over the U.S.
policy on issues in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
