<HEADLINE> Nigeria Urged to Release Convicted Coup Plotters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Special
Rapporteur, Soli Sorabjee, has called on the Nigerian government
to release convicted coup plotters including former Chief of
General Staff General Oladjpo Diya, The Punch said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official told a press briefing Tuesday that the
judicial process which tried them had been identified to be
faulty, and the government should release all of them without
exception.
</P>
<P>
Sorabjee who rounded off his week-long investigations of the
human rights situation in Nigeria said that the human rights
situation in the country had improved, compared with what it was
during the regime of the late General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Following his investigations and interaction with human rights
bodies in the country, he noted that the transition program on
course in the west African country is credible.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned, the May 29, 1999 handover date must be
kept, as the contrary would attract international condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The India-born attorney said that he was returning to his home
country of India to prepare, analyze, evaluate and arrive at
conclusions on his investigations for presentation before the
U.N. Human Rights Convention to be held in Geneva in the first
quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
In April this year when the convention was held, Sorabjee
condemned the General Abacha regime for its serious human rights
abuse and political repression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
