<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corruption in Africa Turns off U.S. Firms: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Corruption remained one
of the greatest obstacles to U.S. investment in Africa despite
the continent's achievements in economic and political reforms,
U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley has warned.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a high-level southern Africa trade and investment
summit in Cape Town Tuesday, Daley said although Africa has made
positive moves toward economic reform, political freedom and a
more prosperous consumer, corruption was still a major stumbling
block for U.S. companies doing business here.
</P>
<P>
Failure to respect intellectual property rights was also an
obstacle to attracting offshore investment, especially if Africa
wanted to attract hi-tech companies, Business Day paper Wednesday
quoted Daley as saying.
</P>
<P>
Daley, leading a trade delegation of 15 U.S. business leaders
to the region, said trade between Africa and the United States
had lagged considerably behind U.S. trade with other parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
In effect, if trade had grown between Africa and the United
States as it did between the United States and other developing
countries in the northern hemisphere, it would be 50 percent more
today, Daley said.
</P>
<P>
While South Africa was the most important U.S. trading partner
in Africa, it ranked only 33rd on the country's list of largest
trading partners, Daley said at the meeting, sponsored by the
International Herald Tribune.
</P>
<P>
He said potential business investors also cared about
infrastructure, tax and investment incentives, privatization
plans and other fundamentals of government policies in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Daley said there was an urgent need to speed up regional
integration if Africa wanted to be on the global stage.
</P>
<P>
"For Africa to be on a global stage, it cannot be small
disconnected markets, it must be regional markets... I believe
you need to reduce the trade barriers with your neighbors," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Daley warned that the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) was not moving fast enough to implement its 1996 agreement
to create a free trade zone within eight years.
</P>
<P>
So far only five of the SADC's 14 member countries have
ratified the trade protocol, a first step toward free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
Daley said only 13 percent African trade is with other African
countries whereas two thirds of Europe's trade is with other
European nations and 30 percent Asia's trade is within that
continent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Daley, accompanied by U.S. executives from
AT&AMP;T, the telecommunications group, Coca-Cola and Cargill, signed
an agreement with South African Trade Minister Alec Erwin to
promote investment between U.S. and South African companies.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki told the summit
that Africa struggled to attract investment because of an image
associated with coups and instability.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said a key objective was to achieve regional economic
integration. "All of us know we will only grow when we have
closer integration in the region," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
