<HEADLINE> Two More S. African Ministers to Quit Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Two more South African
cabinet ministers have announced to quit government after 1999
general election, the Star daily published here reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Joe Modise (69) and Education Minister
Sibusiso Bengu (64) Tuesday told the public that they would not
want to be re-elected to parliament next year.
</P>
<P>
Kgalema Motlanthe, secretary-general the ruling African
National Congress (ANC), has confirmed the report.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela, 80, is due to step
down after next year's election. He gave up his ANC chairmanship
last fall.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, now ANC chairman,
is expected to be elected as state president of the country.
</P>
<P>
Last month, ANC veteran, Transport Minister Mac Maharaj
declared publicly that he would not participate in 1999 elections
due to be held in May.
</P>
<P>
In addition, several other ministers, who played key roles in
the anti-apartheid struggle and in the negotiations that led to
the Government of National Unity, are set to retire.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that among those likely to leave political
arena were South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo,
Intelligence Services Deputy Minister Joe Nhlanhla and Public
Enterprises Minister Stella Sigcau.
</P>
<P>
ANC insiders said that Nzo had "hinted long ago" of his
intention to step down. He was expected to make an announcement
soon. Nhlanhla and Sigcau were also expected to announce their
intentions soon.
</P>
<P>
Water Affairs and Forestry Minister Kader Asmal, who is
suffering from cancer, may also not serve in the next cabinet,
although he has said he will be available, ANC insiders said.
</P>
</TEXT>
