officials or with Mr. Tan, and this time I will see to it that I
will call for them and have a meeting with them," he said in the
interview, which was published by the presidential office
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that he wants PAL to continue flying as many
businesses and sectors will suffer once it closes down.
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated his promise to PAL employees that he
will do everything to protect their jobs as long as he is
president.
</P>
<P>
PAL has yet to reach a deal with Cathay, one of at least two
major foreign airlines interested in buying into the Philippine
flag carrier. The Other is U.S.-based Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that talks between PAL and Cathay recently
hit a snag due to the alleged plan of Cathay to retrench PAL
employees.
</P>
<P>
But Cathay has since denied having imposed such condition for
its entry into the financially troubled airline.
</P>
<P>
PAL closed down on September 23 after talks between its
management and workers collapsed, and resumed operation early
October after President Estrada managed to convince the workers to
accept the management's offer of 20 percent equity and three board
seats in the airline, in return for a 10-year suspension of their
collective bargaining agreement. 
</P>
