<HEADLINE> G-77 High-level Conference Opens in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas Wednesday called on South-South cooperation countries to
improve their solidarity.
</P>
<P>
opening the Group of 77's high-level conference on regional
and sub-regional cooperation in Nusa Dua, Bali province,
Indonesia, the minister said the solidarity among South-South
cooperation countries is important in facing globalization,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
He said that dialog and partnership with advanced countries
are also important.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to issue two main documents -- the
Bali Declaration and the Bali Action Plan, which will recommend
concrete steps to increase regional and sub-regional cooperation
under the South-South framework, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The conference, to be held from December 2 to 5, also aims to
draw up a recommendation for the South-South summit to be held in
Havana in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference is being attended by ministers and
ranking officials of 132 countries, representatives of
international organizations, and observers from Canada, Japan and
South Korea. A delegation from China also attends the meeting at
the invitation of the organizers.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 77 was founded on June 15, 1964 after 77 countries
signed a joint declaration in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral economic cooperation organization has since
increased its membership to 133 countries in Africa, Asia, the
Caribbean and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia was appointed leader for 1998 during the group's 1997
meeting in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
