<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Urges People to Watch Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Wednesday told the people to stay vigilant against
anarchists and nihilists who sow destruction in the country.
</P>
<P>
"I dare convey this message to the people to increase their
vigilance. Leave out all negative thinking and prejudices," the
president told members of the Union of Youths Continuing the
Struggle of the Republic of Indonesia, whom he received at the
presidential office here.
</P>
<P>
The president called for a stop to the destruction of houses of
worship, schools and other public facilities.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Indonesian culture tolerates diversity,
including in the practice of religion.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Habibie condemned the burning and ransacking of
mosques and churches in Ketapang, Central Jakarta, and Kupang,
capital of East Nusa Tenggara province.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn the act, whether it is a church or a mosque or a
temple. We condemn it because it is against the values of our
culture, against the universal values of human rights," the
president said when opening the fourth national workshop on human
rights at the State Palace.
</P>
<P>
he added: "We should not tolerate discrimination in whatever
form, be it racial or ethnic. Indonesia is not a secular state,
not is it a state based upon one religion."
</P>
<P>
National Police chief Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi Tuesday told
reporters that the violence in Kupang Monday was a direct
retaliation against the burning of churches in Jakarta on November
22. Fourteen people were killed and 22 churches and five schools
were burned or vandalized during the clash in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
His spokesman Brig. Gen. Togar M. Sianipar said rioters burned
four mosques, two houses, two shops, three restaurants and two
cars in Kupang. At least 17 people were injured during the riot.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that unrest spread to Banjarsari town, 250
kilometers southwest of Jakarta, Tuesday. Muslim crowds torched
two homes used for Christian worship as well as a shop and a
cinema in the town.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of different religions had reiterated their
condemnation and concern over the incident and urged people to
remain calm.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is 90 percent Muslim and is the world's most populous
Islamic nation. However, some islands in the archipelago have
Christian majorities.
</P>
<P>
Religious diversity based on a belief in God is enshrined in
the national ideology Pancasila (the five basic principles of the
Republic of Indonesia), adopted when Indonesia declared
independence from Dutch colonial rule in 1945.
</P>
<P>
The upsurge in religious violence follows months of riots and
protests in many parts of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
