<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Economy Grows 5% in Year to September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia recorded an
astounding growth rate of five percent in the 12 months to
September in the face of Asian economic crisis, the Australian
Bureau of Statistics said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) figures released by the bureau
Wednesday showed growth in the September quarter was driven by
strong domestic demand with increases in private consumption and
business investment.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed seasonally adjusted GDP rose by 1.0 percent
in the three months to September, resulting in an annual growth
rate of 5.0 percent, a figure much better than most people
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the growth figures showed the continued
momentum and resilience of the local economy and highlighted an
enviable combination of strong growth and low inflation, which has
been well below 2 percent during the past year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Asian economic crisis and close trade link with
Asia, Australia's exports of goods and services in the past
financial year ending on June 30, 1998, grew by 8.2 percent over
the previous year, thanks to good growth in exports to the United
States and Europe and some emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
Su-Lin Ong, an economist with RBC DS Global Markets, said low
interest rates and accommodative monetary policy, low inflation
and continued employment and wages growth have been important in
underpinning domestic demand and overall growth.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates, including banks' lending interest rates, home
loan interest rates, are the lowest for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
But two hours before the bureau released the figures, the
Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA), the country's central bank,
announced a reduction in the cash rate to 4.75 percent from 5.00
percent, citing an expected slowdown in growth next year and low
inflation as reasons for the move.
</P>
<P>
A fall in cash rate, the interest rate on overnight loans made
between institutions in the money market, would lead to cuts in
other interest rates, including banks' lending interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Australia's economy grew by 3.9 percent during the financial
year of 1997-1998, ending on June 30, 1998, and the federal
government predicted in September that the growth rate for the
current financial year would be 2.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
"With a significant decline in world growth predicted by most
forecasters, it is still likely that growth in Australia will
slow, at least temporarily, during 1999," said Ian Macfarlane,
governor of the central bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
