<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Higher After Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar bounced
higher Wednesday, defying the early pressure of a cut in interest
rates by the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) to gain two thirds
of a U.S. cent.
</P>
<P>
With lower rates usually a negative for the local currency, the
market focused instead on the small size of the monetary policy
easing with the RBA taking the rare step of reducing rates by only
25 basis points.
</P>
<P>
"It was a positive view taken by the currency market," said
Scott Young, foreign exchange dealer at Arab Bank.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed around its highs at 63.68 U.S. cents,
from 63.01 Tuesday, and traded between 63.00 and 63.70 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The RBA announced a reduction in the cash rate to 4.75 percent
from 5.00 percent, citing an expected slowdown in growth next year
and low inflation as reasons for the move.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates the Australian dollar was buying 77.53
Japanese yen from 77.43 yen Tuesday and 1.0714 German marks from
1.0656 marks.  
</P>
