<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millennium Bug to Cost Bezeq 54 Million U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Bezeq, Israel's largest
telephone company, will spend at least 54 million U.S. dollars to
prepare its computer system for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In its third-quarter financial report released on Wednesday,
Bezeq said the money will be used for conversion and necessary
upgrading of engineering systems, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But the report said there are still potential cost that can not
be estimated at the current stage, such as the employment of extra
manpower needed in the project.
</P>
<P>
The company has just begun work on conversion. Industry sources
say that the longer the company waits, the higher the conversion
cost is likely to be, because it will have to pay higher prices to
get the work done in shorter time.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 problem of computer, which is also called
computer millennium bug, dates back to the early days of computer
programming when only the last two numbers of the year were used
in most softwares.
</P>
<P>
Some computers will read 2000 as 1900 and shut off the computer
systems or give wrong answers when the new century starts.
</P>
<P>
Experts around the world are sparing no efforts to solve the
glitches, but no breakthrough has been reported so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rates Cut Pushes Australian Stocks Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
surged almost one percent Wednesday on the back of a
much-anticipated cut in official interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index stacked on 26.9 points to
2,761.0, coming off a peak of 2,766.2.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously the rates cut this morning has driven our market
today," said Macquarie Nevitts client adviser Steve Mayne.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia announced a 25 basis point
reduction in the cash rate to 4.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the stocks across the board were stronger,
especially the interest-rate sensitive banking stocks.
</P>
<P>
"A few banks moved quickly to lower rates and the market took
that positively," Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian equities market, the all industrials index
climbed 51.3 points to 4,910.3, while the all resources index
firmed 6.4 points to 1,013.0.
</P>
<P>
The banking index jumped 84.3 points to 6,199.1, with sector
heavyweight National Australia Bank leading the way, stacking on
44 cents to 23.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia shot up 36.7 cents to 22.229
Australian dollars, ANZ bank gained 18 cents to 10.45 Australian
dollars on a turnover of 5.99 million shares and Westpac rallied
12 cents to 10.28 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, BHP rose 14.1 cents to 12.42
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index moved 7.6 points higher to 1,122.1 on the
strength of a firming in the price of the precious metal.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney Wednesday afternoon
was 294.25 U.S. dollars an ounce, up from Tuesday's close of
292.95 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 349.01 million shares traded for 719.58
million U.S. dollars, with rising stocks outnumbering falling
stocks by 593 to 512 and 433 stocks remaining steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
