<HEADLINE> Yunnan Rushes Relief to Quake-Stricken City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province has allocated five million yuan (600,000 U.S. dollars)
for relief efforts in Xuanwei, a city hit by an earthquake
measuring 5.1 on the Richter Scale on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Two students attempting to evacuate their classrooms in the
village of Dawu were injured during the quake, with houses and
school buildings sustaining varying levels of damage.
</P>
<P>
Xuanwei is located at the northeastern part of Yunnan
Province and has a population of 1.28 million.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has dispatched a work group to assist
local officials and make arrangements for relief efforts, and
Deputy Governor Niu Shaoyao rushed to the quake-stricken area
on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Niu said the province will expand relief efforts and closely
monitor the situation to accurately predict aftershocks. Four
aftershocks have already been recorded in the Xuanwei area.
</P>
<P>
Two earthquakes measuring 5.0 and 6.2 on the Richter scale hit
the Ninglang Yi Nationality Autonomous County in Yunnan Province
on November 19 killing three and injuring more than 1,500
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
