<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Tea Prices Mixed Amid High Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan tea prices at this
week's auction in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa were mixed
amid good demand, traders have said.
</P>
<P>
"There was good demand but at irregular rates," Norman Wilson,
managing director of Africa Tea Brokers (ATB), was quoted by
Wednesday's Daily Nation as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wilson said Best Pekoes Ones (BP1s) of all categories were
lower, undermined by less demand from Sudan, Yemen and other
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
But other categories were a strong feature and ended often
dearer, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Best Pekoes Ones of all categories sold at irregularly lower
rates, with some withdrawals. Older invoices of brighter and
medium Pekoes Fannings were irregular but on balance sold at
around last auction's rates," he said in an ATB report.
</P>
<P>
"Fresher teas appreciated by five and 15 U.S. cents," the
report added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan packers and traders lent the market good support
while Britain was more active, although it bought selectively in
line with quality, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
There was also improved inquiry from Egypt for Pekoes Dusts
and Dust Ones.
</P>
<P>
Among the broken teas, or the lower end of the market, Yemen,
Sudan and other Middle East buyers were not very active, which
resulted in lower prices.
</P>
<P>
Wilson said that the market had already taken into account
record Kenyan tea output of around 280 million kg this year
compared with 220 million kg in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He added that the only worry now was a possible crop level
beyond the forecast figure, which could trigger a drop in prices.
</P>
<P>
Exports of tea, coffee and horticultural produce are the main
source of foreign exchange earnings for Kenya following the
recession of the tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
They are also responsible for the stable trading of the
Shillings in the money market.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the weekly tea auction held on every Monday are
done in U.S. Dollars ensuring a constant flow of Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
