<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Judicial System Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- China plans to comprehensively
restructure its judicial system during 1999 by further opening
courtrooms to the general public, increasing independent trial
responsibility of judges and establishing a people's jury system.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang, president of the Supreme People's Court (SPC),
outlined the reform plan today at a national conference of
presidents of higher people's courts at the provincial level.
</P>
<P>
"Judicial reform is part of ongoing political restructuring in
China," said Xiao, adding that the goal of the reform is to ensure
justice throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
Open court trials represent a constitutional principle
contained in the nation's criminal, civil and administrative
procedures laws. However, various factors have precluded vigorous
implementation of the principle, including the proficiency levels
of judges.
</P>
<P>
Members of the general public are sometimes refused entry to a
public hearing due to the "lack of seating."
</P>
<P>
Xiao said that all court trials procedures must be open to the
public beginning next year, including the presentation,
deliberation and verification of evidence, as well as legal
arguments and the announcement of verdicts.
</P>
<P>
"Verdicts must be made public in a timely manner in order to
avoid under-the-table deals," said Xiao.
</P>
<P>
Reform will also focus on the form of verdicts, Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
"Current verdicts are rendered in similar simplistic wording,
with no explanation concerning the confirmation of evidence and
application of the law" said Xiao. He added that verdicts fail to
cite grounds for conclusions reached by judges.
</P>
<P>
"Verdicts should help the general public understand the legal
system and ensure the authority of the courts," according to
Xiao.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Official Calls for Better Relations with Foreign Parties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) said here today the CPC should
cultivate better relations with foreign parties at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
Dai Bingguo, head of the International Department of the CPC
Central Committee, was speaking at a seminar on the 20th
anniversary of the convening of the third plenary session of the
11th CPC Central Committee in 1978, which kicked off the policy
of reform and opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
He said that the CPC International Department should make
profound studies of and carry out Deng Xiaoping's theory of
diplomacy and the foreign policy set at the CPC's 15th National
Congress so as to improve the party's relations with foreign
parties in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Dai noted that the 3rd plenary session marks the beginning of
a fundamental change in the guiding theory, aims, policy and
principles of the Party's foreign relations work.
</P>
<P>
"The past two decades have witnessed a remarkable rise of
CPC's international status and influence as well as a vigorous
expansion of CPC's foreign relations," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the communist movement suffered severe
setbacks internationally and the world situation has changed
dramatically over the past 20 years, the foreign relations of the
CPC has experienced a vigorous growth rather than shrinking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Official Calls for Better Relations with Foreign Parties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The head of the CPC International Department vowed to make
earnest efforts to further improve the Party's foreign relations
through summarizing the achievements and experiences of the
Party's foreign relations work since the 3rd plenary session of
the 11th Party Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
"That is to say, we must attain more fruits in the development
of new types of exchanges and cooperative relations with foreign
parties so as to improve state-to-state relations," Dai said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Judicial System Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reform will also focus on strengthening the role judges play in
independent trials. Xiao said all cases will be handled by
judicial panels free of interference from above, with the
exception of difficult major cases which will be decided by
judicial committees.
</P>
<P>
Existing procedures require that court officials at different
levels ratify court judgements prior to pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
Xiao said that the nominal "people's jury system" is seldom
used because of numerous unresolved issues.
</P>
<P>
He said the SPC and National People's Congress Standing
Committee are currently discussing laws governing the
qualifications, selection, rights and duties and qualifications of
jurors.
</P>
<P>
A system allowing courts to invite specialists and experts with
appropriate expertise to serve as jurors in cases involving
specialized industries and knowledge, said Xiao.
</P>
<P>
He urged local courts to experiment with reform in line with
the Constitution and related laws.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 Beijing courts above the county level and 57 at the
township level have opened courtrooms to public hearings, with
members of the general public required to present a valid ID to
gain admittance.
</P>
<P>
The "open trial" movement is in fact being carried out across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
Xiao also addressed judicial work for the coming year and noted
that courts must adhere to the political orientation based on
safeguarding the nation's reform, development and stability, as
well as improving both internal and external checks and balances
ensuring justice.
</P>
<P>
Information released during today's conference revealed that
Chinese courts at all levels have concluded 3.82 million of 4.33
million cases of first instance during the first ten months. Said
figures represent respective 2.67 percent and 0.93 percent
increases on the 1997 period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0162 </DOCNO>
