<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps Up Oil And Gas Development In Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- China's largest offshore oil
production area in the Bohai Sea expects to have 60 million tons
of verified oil reserves and 10 billion cu.m. of natural gas this
year.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Shaodong, president of the China Offshore Oil
Bohai Corp (COOBC), Bohai has an annual oil output of 2.2 million
tons and gas output of 370 million cubic meters. He said China is
speeding up efforts to explore two large oilfields there to add 4
million tons of crude annually.
</P>
<P>
He said that oil from the Qinhuangdao 32-6 and Nanbao 35-2
oilfields will be piped inland through the port of Jingtang in
Hebei province. Qinhuangdao 32-6, 100 kilometers east of Tianjin,
has 170 million tons of proven oil reserves. Eleven wells have
been drilled there.
</P>
<P>
Nanbao 35-2, some 20 kilometers south of Tangshan, has proven
reserves of 70 million tons. Four test wells have been
drilled. Nanbao's reserves have been estimated at 110 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The distance between the two oilfields is just 20 kilometers,
making joint development in a 70-sq.km. area possible.
</P>
<P>
Seven standard platforms will be put up in the two oilfields
and two pipelines laid to transport oil inland. Terminals will
also be built at the port of Jingtang, with 650 meters of the
coast used for oil transport berths. The construction work is
expected to cost 7.29 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A Palestinian man was stabbed to death Wednesday
morning in East Jerusalem and initial investigations by police
indicate a political motive behind the incident.
</P>
<P>
The 41-year old victim was stabbed to death early Wednesday by
an Israeli Jew in the Old City of Jerusalem. The police said the
attacker wanted to cause political problems in the city. The
police, who gave no further details about the incident, said the
investigation is still underway. (Israel-Stabbing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MADRID -- Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar told visiting
Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza Tuesday that his
government will respect Britain's forthcoming decision on the
extradition of Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Aznar said the Spanish government believed right from the
beginning that the Pinochet issue should be decided by the justice
department. His government will adhere to this position and
respect the decision of judicial authorities. Insulza said he was
satisfied with his trip to Madrid, noting that after his talks in
Madrid there have appeared "optimistic signs" that will help
settle the Pinochet issue. (Spain-Chile-Pinochet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- Top legislators of the 15 members of the European
Union (EU) and the European Parliament gathered here Tuesday for a
one-day meeting on the parliament's role in Europe's integration
process.
</P>
<P>
Austrian National Council Speaker Heinz Fischer said in his
opening speech that it was very important to discuss Europe's
cooperation and development from the parliamentary point of
view. He also noted that this meeting, being held before an EU
summit next month, would focus on an exchange of opinions, rather
than adopting any resolution. (EU-Parliament-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia Tuesday condemned certain countries for
contacting the "Kosovo Liberation Army," an illegal armed group of
ethnic Albanian separatists fighting for independence of the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum sent to the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav
Jovanovic described the contacts as the application of "double
standards" on the Kosovo issue. The contacts were "part of the
double-standard policy that aims to support the terrorist
organization in Kosovo and legalize it gradually," said
Jovanovic. (Yugoslavia-OSCE-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
