<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Put on High Alert for Turkish-Italian Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish government has called
on over 22,000 policemen to protect the security for the
politically tinged European Champions' League match on Wednesday
between Turkish champion Galatasaray and Italy's Juventus in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Interior Minister Kutlu Aktas was quoted by local
press as saying that "We will do our best to start and finish the
game without any incidents."
</P>
<P>
The tight security measures were guarantees requested by
Juventus and UEFA to protect the Italian side from any possible
acts of violence by Turkish fans angry at Italy's refusal to
extradite Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Aktas said that police will use a heavy hand against
troublemakers, warning that "whoever gets involved in provocative
acts will be severely punished."
</P>
<P>
Security officials said that police motorcades will escort the
Italian team from Ataturk International Airport to its hotel and
to Ali Sami Yen Stadium in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Helmeted anti-riot police with batons and shields will be
stationed in and around the stadium to make certain that the
match is carried out in an orderly fashion.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that police will search spectators entering the
stadium for knives and clubs, banners and fireworks will also be
banned and roads to be used by Juventus players will be cordoned
off.
</P>
<P>
The game is expected to be played after a one-week
postponement by UEFA for security concerns on the wake of the
anti-Italian sentiment in Turkey over Romes' failure to extradite
Ocalan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
