<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Fall Further in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Interest rates in Kenya's
domestic money market continued the downward trend with the
average new rate for the 91-day Treasury Bills standing at 15.79
percent.
</P>
<P>
This reflects a drop of 1.11 percent from that recorded in the
previous auction, according to the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)'s
weekly update on economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
The interbank borrowing rate recorded a sharp decline at 10.65
percent level in the week ending November 27. Commercial banks'
average base lending rates dropped from 26.85 percent in November
to 26.20 with effect from December 1.
</P>
<P>
The central bank report further noted that the local Shilling
weakened against the U.S. Dollar during this week's opening of
trading.
</P>
<P>
The Dollar was exchanging at 59.89 Shillings as opposed to the
previous week's exchange rate of 59.55 Shillings, the East
African Standard newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the slight drop against the Dollar, the Shilling on
average strengthened against the Pound Sterling to exchange at
98.99 Shillings from 99.17 Shillings recorded in the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
Overall inflation rate remained in the single digit level
during November. The three-month annualize rate rose to negative
3.2 percent last month from negative 2.4 percent in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
