<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Airports Target 8 Million Travelers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan airports are expected
to handle eight million passengers in the next five years, while
profits are expected to double by 2000, the Kenya Airport
Authority (KAA) officials say.
</P>
<P>
Janet Ongera, KAA's Managing Director, said that through
aggressive marketing and other measures, KAA plans to increase
the number of passengers handled in Kenyan airports from the
current four million.
</P>
<P>
"KAA recognizes the need to promote good international trade
ties and that is why we are prepared to double our services for
the collection of national revenue," Ongera was quoted by
Wednesday's East African Standard as saying.
</P>
<P>
She said that another objective to meet the challenges of the
next millennium is to increase the freight handled through Kenyan
airports from the current 800,000 tons to two million tons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a meeting on the review of the civil aviation
policy, Ongera proposed that to achieve the goals, KAA should
improve the standards of customer service to international
standards.
</P>
<P>
She said that insecurity both in air and at the airports have
been the major bottleneck to Kenya's tourism trade and asked the
government to "be thorough" in guaranteeing safety.
</P>
<P>
She also called for the full use of all airstrips in Kenya,
saying that many airstrips receive very low traffic mainly for
administrative purpose and are not viable to operate.
</P>
<P>
"Only about seven airstrips -- Musiara, Keekorok, Mara Serena,
Nanyuki, Mandera, Lokichogio and Amboseli -- are commercially
viable," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
