<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded in Tokyo
Wednesday following losses over the previous three trading days,
but the overall gains were limited by a lack of buying incentives.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 151.21 points, or 1.02
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 14,986.62.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all First Section
issues, added 4.89 points, or 0.43 percent, to 1,147.15.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on major sections dropped to an estimated 311 million
shares from 393.42 million shares on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 743 to 418, with 135 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The market's concern about further deterioration of the economy
made players hesitant to buy shares aggressively, while they
remained reluctant to sell them as Japan's financial system has
gradually regained stability, an analyst said.
</P>
<P>
Traders, who are now focusing on the course of coalition talks
between the ruling Liberal Democratic Party and the Liberal Party,
say the market is seeking stronger political leadership to pull
the economy out of the current slump. 
</P>
</TEXT>
