<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Government to Offer Farmers More Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government said
that it has temporarily suspended the new agricultural policy and
will not leave the agriculture sector completely in private
hands.
</P>
<P>
Acting Agriculture Minister Suresh Desai told parliament
Tuesday that there is need for a strong government involvement in
agriculture especially at the transitional level of the new
policy, Wednesday's Times of Zambia quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new policy under which the government has completely
withdrawn from the delivery of inputs, credit provision and
marketing of produce has created problems in the agricultural
sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there will be more direct involvement in the sector
from government wings such as the Food Reserve Agency from now
onwards.
</P>
<P>
He said that "economic survival for the country lies in
farming. Unless government runs away from a liberalized
agriculture, we will be doomed. We will be entering the next
millennium begging for food." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
