<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, Ethiopia to Beef Up Border Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan and Ethiopian
governments have resolved to beef up security on their common
border where bandits swept across from Ethiopia into northeastern
Kenya in October.
</P>
<P>
The two governments reached agreement Tuesday to increase
entry points along their common borders to effectively monitor
and maintain laws and order there, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They also said in a joint communique that there was need for
regular exchange of security information at the border points.
</P>
<P>
About 140 people were killed, 52 villagers kidnaped and about
17,500 head of cattle were stolen in Kenya's Wajir District
during the October attack by some 500 Oromo bandits from
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came at the end of three days of peace talks
between top security officials from the two sides in Masinga,
northeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Northeastern Provincial Commissioner Maurice Makhanu
led the Kenyan delegation while the 18-member Ethiopian team was
led by the deputy commissioner of the federal police, Major
Alemseged G.Yohannes.
</P>
<P>
The delegates proposed that similar talks be held twice a year
and fixed the next-meeting for April next year in Bahr-Dar in
Ethiopia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
