<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Foreign Currency Reserves Hit New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel's foreign currency
reserves in November rised to 22.479 billion U.S. dollars,
crossing the mark of 22 billion U.S. dollars, according to the
figures released by the Bank of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The November figure is 565 million higher than that of October.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Israel, the country's central bank, attributed the
increase mainly to the receipt of the annual civilian aid package
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
In November, the volume of public foreign currency transactions
fell signigficantly to 13.41 billion U.S. dollars, compared with
19.35 billion U.S. dollars in October, the bank said
</P>
<P>
The October volume was unusually high, due to Israel's
currency the shekel's rapid depreciation during that month. In
September, trading volume was similar to November's level, at
13.16 Billion U.S. dolllars.
</P>
<P>
The daily average of foreign currency transactions was 639
million U.S. dollars in November, down from 968 million in
october, the bank added.
</P>
<P>
The volume of the central bank's currency transactions with
the commercial banks also returned to normal in November,
totalling 1.753 billion U.S. dollars. The daily average of these
deals was 83 million, down from 150 million U.S. dollars in
October.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also said that the shekel gained against both
the dollar and the currency basket in November. During the month,
the currency basket fell 2.5 percent, to 4.5537 shekels, and the
dollar fell 1.39 percent, to 4.1910 shekels a dollar.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of this year, however, the currency basket
has risen 22.35 percent against the shekel, in annual terms,
while the dollar has risen 20.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Israel's foreign currency reserves was
20.3 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
