<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Continue To Drop Through Historic Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices continued
to fall through historic lows Tuesday on U.S. market as world oil
producers were unable to reach an agreement to cut supplies.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the New York Mercantile Exchange show that crude
oil for delivery in January fell nine cents to 11.13 U.S. dollars
a barrel, setting a new historic low for the second day in a row.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, January crude oil finished at 11.22 dollars a
barrel, when adjusted for inflation, hitting a record low point
since 1959, when the U.S. government started tracking oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Traders said oil markets were handing down their verdict on the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) for its
inability to cut on supplies at last week's meeting in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said supplies must be cut by 1-1.5 million barrels per
day to stabilize prices at the 12-13 dollars range. Now 75 million
barrels are out daily, with OPEC members accounting for 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Traders said there could be a scrap for market share among the
OPEC members, rather than another round of the supply cuts agreed
earlier in the year. That could point to single-digit oil prices
in coming weeks or months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
