<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Affirms Achievements of 1998 APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
has affirmed the achievements of the APEC leaders' informal
meeting in Kuala Lumpur last month, saying "leaders of 21 regional
economies affirmed their commitment to the APEC process and
introduced new initiatives to its work program".
</P>
<P>
In a statement the New Zealand APEC Task Force (ATF) said
Wednesday that the key outcome of the 1998 APEC leaders' informal
meeting was the "refusal of the leaders to embrace protectionist
responses to the economic crisis. Instead all 21 regional
economies reaffirmed their commitment to the APEC process and its
vision of free and open trade and investment".
</P>
<P>
The ATF, a body organized by the New Zealand government to
prepare for the 1999 APEC meetings in the country, noted that
Japan's decision not to commit to firm deadlines on removal of
trade barriers in fish and forestry "was wrongly interpreted as a
failure for APEC, reflecting general misunderstandings about the
process and its potential".
</P>
<P>
"In fact, good progress was made on the Early Voluntary
Sectoral Liberalization (EVSL) program. Tariff removal dates of
December 2004 for forestry and December 2005 for fish, introduced
by ministers in Kuching this year, were confirmed by leaders in
Kuala Lumpur. All 16 economies participating in EVSL, including
Japan, endorsed these dates," it said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
With regard to financial issues, it added, there had been
concerns before the meeting that the pressures created by the
economic crisis would cause some member economies to pull back
from the APEC goals and seek to return to protectionist
responses.
</P>
<P>
In the event this did not happen. The Leaders' Declaration
reaffirmed APEC's fundamental goals, including its vision of free
and open trade and investment by 2010/2020. The Declaration
emphasized prudent growth-oriented macroeconomic policies,
strengthened financial institutions and markets, trade and
investment liberalization and capacity building, ATF said.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, ATF said the task of accommodating visitors
at next September's APEC 1999 leaders' informal meeting in
Auckland, the largest city in New Zealand, is well underway.
</P>
<P>
On the accommodation front, planning began in January this year
and all is running to schedule, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
