<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Proceed with Leasing of F16 Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
has decided not to buy a third frigate from Australia, but would
"proceed with leasing 28 eight-year-old F16 aircraft from the
United States to replace the 19 aging Skyhawks", the Evening Post
Wednesday quoted New Zealand Defense Minister Max Bradford as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"The deal will avoid the need to spend 54 million NZ dollars
(28.6 million U.S. dollars) upgrading the Skyhawk fleet which is
due to be replaced in 2007, and save New Zealand 431 million NZ
dollars (228 million U.S. dollars) over the life of the American
jets compared with purchasing new aircraft next century," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The government would also proceed with a 500 million NZ dollar
(265 million U.S. dollar) re-equipment program for the New Zealand
Army, which would grow by 500 soldiers with the addition of two
rifle companies, Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
"The total package will add not one NZ dollar to the defense
re-equipment capital plan announced in October, nor will it take
one NZ dollar away," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These decisions prove that we are committed to maintaining a
credible defense force in order to pull our weight with our close
friends and allies," the defense minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper also quoted New Zealand Prime
Minister Jenny Shipley as saying the offer of the F16s, which
"ideally suit New Zealand's needs", is "overwhelmingly
advantageous" and will not be repeated in the future.
</P>
<P>
While politics and public attitude to a third frigate purchase
have been factors, the Cabinet has put the greatest emphasis on
keeping within budget and sticking to the priorities identified in
 last year's Defense Assessment, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
