<HEADLINE> New Zealand "Emerging from Recession": Economic Forecasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand will record
negative economic growth of 0.9 percent for the year to March
1999, instead of 1.5 percent contraction predicted earlier, and
is already emerging from its recession, according to Deutsche
Bank.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic forecasts out Wednesday, the bank said
New Zealand will notch two quarters of positive growth in the
second half of this year, with the recovery projected to gather
pace in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Official figures, which were released earlier, showed the
country's gross domestic product decreased by 0.8 percent in the
second quarter of this year following one percent fall in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Bank forecast growth rates of 0.2 percent and 0.4
percent for the third and fourth quarters respectively. It also
sees growth of 2.6 percent in the year to March 2000, accelerating
to 4 percent in 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
"That will be based on a consolidating international growth
outlook, as well as significant domestic policy stimulus," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The bank forecast the unemployment rate in New Zealand will
peak at 8.5 percent in mid-1999 and inflation at 2.2 percent in
late 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
