<HEADLINE> Spain Reiterates Respect for British Decision on Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Spanish Prime Minister Jose
Maria Aznar told visiting Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel
Insulza Tuesday that his government will respect Britain's
forthcoming decision on the extradition of Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Aznar said the Spanish government believed right from the
beginning that the Pinochet issue should be decided by the justice
department. His government will adhere to this position and
respect the decision of judicial authorities.
</P>
<P>
Insulza, who arrived here from London Monday, had talks with
Aznar, his Spanish counterpart Abel Matutes, Defense Minister
Eduardo Serra Rexach and other Spanish government officials.
</P>
<P>
He said he was satisfied with his trip to Madrid, noting that
after his talks in Madrid there have appeared "optimistic signs"
that will help settle the Pinochet issue. But he refused to
explain what these signs were.
</P>
<P>
He also said he neither made nor received any commitment on the
Pinochet issue.
</P>
<P>
Insulza flew back to his country Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Chilean former president Pinochet, who was arrested on October
16 in Britain at the request of a Spanish judge, is currently
under police guard in London while awaiting a decision on whether
Britain would extradite him to Spain.
</P>
<P>
Spanish judge Baltasar Garzon has blamed Pinochet for the death
or disappearance of more than 3,000 people, including Spanish
immigrants, during his 1973-1990 rule of Chile. 
</P>
