<HEADLINE> Mexico, Switzerland to Cooperate on Salinas Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Swiss authorities will give
their Mexican counterparts the results of their three-year
investigation of Raul Salinas, brother of former Mexican president
Carlos Salinas.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo,
visiting Swiss Attorney General Carla del Ponte said on Tuesday
that investigators would give Mexicans evidence that Raul Salinas
accepted protection money from drug lords.
</P>
<P>
Del Ponte arrived in Mexico on Monday from Brazil to meet with
Madrazo and organize the transfer of documents gathered by Swiss
investigators until October 20.
</P>
<P>
The documents reportedly proved that Raul used his influence
during his brother's 1988-1994 term to launder drug money.
</P>
<P>
Swiss authorities accused Salinas of money laundering based on
the testimonies of Drug Enforcement Administration witnesses under
a U.S. protection program. The Swiss seized over 114 million
U.S. dollars in bank accounts opened by Salinas.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report quoted Valentin Roschacher, chief of
Switzerland's anti-drug police, as saying investigators concluded
that Colombia's Medellin and Cali drug cartels as well as Mexican
traffickers paid Raul Salinas at least 500 million dollars over 10
years to protect drug shipments through Mexico. 
</P>
