<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Set Up Industrial Park in Chittagong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- An industrial park involving 540
million U.S. dollars is to be set up in Bangladesh's second
largest city of Chittagong, 224 kilometers southeast of here,
early next year by a local private firm.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Chittagong Industrial Park Ltd., the second of its
kind in the private sector, has already obtained approval from a
high-powered cell at the prime minister's office, The Financial
Express Wednesday quoted the park's chairman, Quayum Chowdhury, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The park, which will be built for setting up 100-percent
export-oriented industries owned by both local and foreign
investors, will be developed on 42.6 hectares of land in Rangunia,
30 kilometers from the Chittagong port, with an estimated
investment of 120 million U.S. dollars, the park chief said.
</P>
<P>
"We are now conducting contour and topographic surveys in the
area, and the main work of developing infrastructure will begin in
April 1999," he added.
</P>
<P>
The park will have 400 industrial plots and facilities for
housing and recreation of the workers and employees, he stated.
</P>
<P>
The area would later be expanded to 300 hectares with further
investment, he said, adding that negotiation was going on with
several foreign investors for the expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Youngone company was the first to initiate such a
venture in the private sector following the country's enactment of
the Private Export Processing Act in 1996 that paved the way for
private investment in industrial parks.
</P>
<P>
Work on the park developed by the Youngone company in
Chittagong with an estimated investment of 200 million dollars is
still going on, and the park will have 200 industrial plots and
other facilities when finished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
