<HEADLINE> Mexico Calls for Coordinated Anti-Drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's Federal Attorney
General Jorge Madrazo Tuesday called for concerted international
efforts against narcotics, citing that growing sophistication of
drug smugglers made it impossible for a single country to fight
them.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Mexico-Spain seminar on the role of the mass media
in anti-drug campaigns, Jorge Madrazo said that drug cartels do
not feel limited by borders, ignoring the concepts of sovereignty,
the rule of law and the institutions.
</P>
<P>
He said Mexican drug traffickers routinely commit other crimes
such as money laundering and arms trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Madrazo said that the traffickers also spread corruption and
committed homicides with the "truly infernal" capacity for
violence.
</P>
<P>
He said Mexico supported the creation in the short term of a
multi-country evaluation mechanism for drugs in the Organization
of American States, rejecting the annual certification of the
United States on other countries' anti-drug efforts.
</P>
<P>
Madrazo said that such certification comes from "unilateral,
partial and biased evaluations" based on "internal political games
which have nothing to do with us." 
</P>
