<HEADLINE> India Increases Imports of Edible Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- With the steady increase in
imports of edible oil since the 1992-93 season, the rate of
self-sufficiency in edible oil in India has fallen sharply to 77
percent in the 1997-98 season from the peak level of 97 percent in
1997-98, official sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the 1997-98 season, self-sufficiency rate in production
of edible oil declined to 77 percent from 81 percent in 1996-97.
Production of oilseeds during 1997-98 fell sharply to 23.69
million tons from 24.96 million tons in 1996-97. Similarly,
domestic edible oil availability in the 1997-98 season also
declined to 7 million tons from 7.42 million tons in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, imports of edible oil into the country
touched an all time high of 2.083 million tons during 1997-98,
surpassing the earlier peak level of 1.82 million tons during
1987-88.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a good sign for the country's oilseed economy and
its farmers and is leading to stagnancy in oilseeds production,"
said Ajay Tandon, president of Solvent Extractors' Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
