<HEADLINE> Workshop on ASEAN Mining Sector Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A workshop is being held here to
 promote investment and protect the environment in the mining
sector of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The two-day workshop, which began on Tuesday, was jointly
sponsored by the Metal Mining Agency of Japan, the United Nations
Industrial Development Organization, Investment Promotion Service
Tokyo, the Japanese Overseas Development Corporation, Bangkok and
the Myanmar Ministry of Mines(MMM).
</P>
<P>
A total of over 150 officials from the ministries concerned,
resource persons of ASEAN countries and personnel of joint-venture
with MMM are attending the workshop.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is aimed at producing suggestions and approaches
for enhancing mineral exploration in the Asian region without
causing harm to the environment.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Mining Law was enacted in 1994 which allowed
foreign entrepreneurs to engage in prospecting and production of
mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
The MMM has been cooperating with foreign firms to conduct
prospecting and exploration for gold and copper in the country
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the agreements for prospecting and exploration,
eight foreign firms have also formed joint ventures with the
departments and enterprises under the MMM.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more than a dozen foreign companies including
those from Australia, Canada, Japan, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand
and the United States have been participating in mineral
extraction in Myanmar, with Canadian companies specializing in
copper mining.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, foreign investment in
Myanmar's mining sector amounted to 501.36 million U.S. dollars in
43 related projects at the end of May this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics also show that the output value of
Myanmar's mining sector rose 1.5 percent in the 1997-98 fiscal
year which ended in March as compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in October, a national workshop, organized by the
Myanmar National Commission for Environmental Affairs and the
Hanns Seidel Foundation of Germany, was held here to propose a
national framework environmental legislation and an environmental
impact assessment legislation for Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
