<HEADLINE> Italy to Provide AIDS Victims with Better Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government will take a
number of steps to improve the living conditions of AIDS victims,
Minister of Health Rosy Bindi announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech here on the occasion of World AIDS Day, she
said the ministry would soon issue regulations, foreseeing
providing babies of HIV-positive women with milk compounds.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will approve a work plan for 1998-2000, under
which more volunteers will be available to provide AIDS patients
with more assistance and doctors will be better prepared for
serving the patients by the most up-to-date medical means, she
said.
</P>
<P>
The country has made some progress in treating this disease and
AIDS vaccine is being tested, said Bindi, adding that at present
the main effective means of curbing AIDS is taking precaution.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that during the period of 1982-1998 about 40,000
HIV/AIDS cases, including 647 children, were found in Italy, of
whom four-fifths were male.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, various activities were held in some Italian cities
on the occasion of World AIDS Day, fixed for December 1 every
year, in order to propagate the knowledge of AIDS and warn people
of this deadly epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
