<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Condemns Countries Contacting Separatists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia Tuesday condemned
certain countries for contacting the "Kosovo Liberation Army," an
illegal armed group of ethnic Albanian separatists fighting for
independence of the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum sent to the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav
Jovanovic described the contacts as the application of "double
standards" on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The contacts were "part of the double-standard policy that aims
to support the terrorist organization in Kosovo and legalize it
gradually," Jovanovic said in the memorandum sent to Polish
Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek, who country holds the rotating
presidency of the OSCE.
</P>
<P>
"Such actions are in violation of basic principles of
international law" and "are to the detriment of the political
process of settling the Kosovo issue by peaceful means,"
Yugoslavia's news agency Tanjug quoted the memorandum as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the news agency did not specify any countries involved.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached between Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke in October, a
2,000-strong OSCE mission force will be deployed in Kosovo to
verify the compliance by the conflicting sides with the
U.N. resolutions on Kosovo, which include the withdrawal of Serb
troops and the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Part of the OSCE mission force is already in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In the memorandum, the Yugoslav foreign minister also listed a
number of recent attacked staged by the separatists on Yugoslav
police and civilians.
</P>
<P>
Between October 13 and November 30, the separatists mounted 310
attacks and provocative operations, killing nine policemen and
wounding 30 others, according to the memorandum.
</P>
<P>
It said the separatists kidnapped three policemen and killed
two of them. Six civilians were also killed in these attacks and
provocative operations, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
