<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela's GDP to Shrink 1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) will shrink by 1 percent this year with an inflation
rate between 30 and 32 percent, Finance Minister Maritza Izaguirre
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Izaguirre said that the decrease was due to an oil price slump
which led to a shortfall of seven billion U.S. dollars in crude
revenues.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Venezuelan economy was boosted by soaring crude
prices of over 16.3 dollars per barrel and by a flow of foreign
investments, registering a 1.5-percent growth.
</P>
<P>
Izaguirre said that she expected a 3-percent growth in 1999,
while annual inflation was going to go down to between 25 and 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
She said that the projected growth was based on higher oil
prices reaching 11.5 dollars per barrel and a crude output of over
three million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
Izaguirre also said that the government was considering
imposing a tax on the consumption of luxury products and liquor.
</P>
<P>
Oil makes up 70 percent of Venezuela's exports and provides
more than 50 percent of the revenue in the national budget.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela produces over three million barrels of crude oil per
day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
