<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, December 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's inflation rate next year will ease to 3.5
percent compared with 8.1 percent this year, the Commerce Ministry
forecast.
</P>
<P>
The forecast implied that Thailand would continue to experience
tight-money conditions in 1999, according to the ministry's
Business Economics Department. (Thailand-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- The Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA), the country's
central bank, announced Wednesday that it had eased monetary
policy, reducing the cash rate by 25 basis points to 4.75 percent
in a bid to boost the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
A fall in cash rate, the interest rate on overnight loans made
between institutions in the money market, would lead to cuts in
other interest rates, including banks' lending interest rates.
(Australia-Rate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The annual inflation rate for the euro-zone
remained stable at one percent between September and October this
year, compared with 1.5 percent a year earlier, the European Union
(EU) said in a report released here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the 15 EU countries' annual inflation
rate, which had stood at 1.7 percent a year earlier, fell from 1.2
percent in September to 1.1 percent in October. (EU-Euro
Zone-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose 0.1
percentage points in October in the United States, the private
research group Conference Board reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The rise, lower than expected but higher than the previous two
months, was due to the stock market rebound and the interest cuts
by the Federal Reserve, the group said. (US-Economic Outlook)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The European Central Bank expects real economic growth
in western Europe to reach just 2.5 percent next year, ECB
President Wim Duisenberg said on Tuesday following a meeting of
top ECB officials in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The figure for 1998 was expected to be 3.0 percent, also below
original expectations, he noted. (EU-Economic Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's trade surplus hit 3.7 billion
U.S. dollars last month, pushing up its gains to 35.9 billion
dollars in the past 11 months, compared with a 10.7-billion
deficit registered during the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's exports in the first 11 months of this year
dropped 2.6 percent to 120.6 billion dollars while imports plunged
37 percent to 84.7 billion dollars, said the Ministry of Commerce,
Industry and Energy. (SKorea-Trade Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia's overall fiscal deficit will be
capped at 6 percent of gross national product (GNP), Bank Negara
(State Bank) Governor Ali Abul Hassan said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government will maintain its track record and will not
resort to monetization to finance the fiscal deficit, Ali Abul
said in a paper presented to the National Outlook Conference
organized by the Malaysian Institute of Economic Research (MIER).
(Malaysia-Deficit) 
