<HEADLINE> Center-Left Bloc Leads in Italy's Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy's center-left bloc emerged
victorious in provincial and municipal elections, preliminary
results showed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The local elections, which started on Sunday, involve more than
15,000 residents in four provinces and 58 towns.
</P>
<P>
The center-left's win was confirmed in provincial councils of
Massa Carrara in central Italy, and Foggia and Benvento in the
south.
</P>
<P>
In the province of Rome, no candidate has obtained more than
half of the votes, but the center-left candidate was ahead of its
main opponent by 4 percentage points. The two will compete after
two weeks in a run-off ballot.
</P>
<P>
Results from municipal elections in the 58 towns produced only
21 outright winners. Of the 21 elected mayors, 14 were supported
by the center-left, six by the center-right and one by the
Northern league.
</P>
<P>
Run-off votes of municipal elections will be held in 36 other
large towns and cities in two weeks. In almost all cases the
run-off will be between the center-left and center-right.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the results, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said
the results of local elections were a "sign of stability" for the
country's political scene.
</P>
<P>
Nearly seven million Italians were eligible to vote for the
local elections in what was billed as a first test for the new
center-left government of D'Alema, who rose to power in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
