<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cleaner Fuel Essential for Emission Controls In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Specialists say that the wider
use of clean fuels is the major way to control auto emissions.
</P>
<P>
General Motors' China branch began a clean fuel drive in
Shanghai this week by bringing together Chinese and international
automobile manufacturing, petroleum, auto service and
environmental protection regulators.
</P>
<P>
Early next year, Beijing and Shanghai will adopt stricter auto
emission standards and China will have similar standards by the
year 2000. Chinese automobile manufacturers are developing
emission controls like electronic fuel injection and catalytic
converters to meet these standards.
</P>
<P>
GM announced recently that it will only bring cars with
catalytic converter into China from now on, and its joint venture
in Shanghai will only produce Buicks with emission controls that
meet the future requirements.
</P>
<P>
Auto industry analysts say that fuel problems in China have
affected the use of new environmental control technology. Zhang
Binyou, of China's biggest auto-manufacturer, the FAW Group, says
that China's oil refineries have yet to produce detergent fuel
additives.
</P>
<P>
China will ban the use of leaded fuel in 2000, but analysts say
that quality standards of unleaded fuel in China are different
from international ones and the difference may hinder the use of
catalytic converters and other devices.
</P>
<P>
An official at a vehicle inspection center in eastern China
says that this lack of quality will cause engines to malfunction,
increasing emission.
</P>
<P>
Du Fangci, of the State Administration of Machine-building
Industry, said that clean fuel is the first step in controlling
car emissions. This means new technology for car manufacturers,
but also the widespread use of cleaner fuels. He said that the
fuel distribution system in China must be reformed to guarantee
quality.
</P>
<P>
According to an international agreement, by 2010 China is
expected to hold the air pollution level to that of Western
countries, and it has adopted a plan to check car emissions at the
1990 level in Europe by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
An environmental protection study has shown that half of
Beijing's air pollution comes from car emissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sir Lanka's Supreme Court Finds Election Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Supreme Court has
found the government's proposed bill to fix new dates for five
Provincial Council elections inconsistent with the constitution.
</P>
<P>
A local newspaper The Island reported Wednesday that the court
has ruled that the bill could be passed only with a special
two-third majority prescribed by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry into the constitutionality of the bill by the
Supreme Court followed hearings of applications filed by four
political parties challenging the legislation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The elections, which were scheduled to be held on August 28 for
five Provincial Councils, were postponed indefinitely by the
government for security reasons on August 4, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The new bill was proposed to enable the Commissioner of
Elections to fix new dates for the elections and to allow the
secretaries of political parties or leaders of independent groups
who have already handed over nominations for the elections to
substitute any names appearing in their respective nomination
papers, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court has determined that both these provisions
were inconsistent with the Constitution, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
