<HEADLINE> Myanmar Forms Fisheries Federation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar formed a fisheries
federation here Tuesday at national level to represent the country
in ASEAN Fishery Federation.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Fisheries Federation (MFF), reformed from the
original Myanmar Aquaculture and Fisheries Association (MAFA),
will cooperate with fellow members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) in fishery resources protection, exchanging
information on the sector, finding new markets for the business
and increasing production and consumption, Lieutenant-General Khin
Nyunt, first secretary of the State Peace and Development Council,
said at the reformation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The fishery sector is the third largest foreign exchange earner
after agriculture and forestry, gaining 167 million U.S. dollars
in the 1997-98 fiscal year, which ended in March, by exporting
over 74,000 tons, up from only 15 million dollars in 1989-90 with
over 9,000 tons of exports, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
He called for endeavors to protect fresh water and sea water
resources to ensure domestic sufficiency and to extend exports and
earn more foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The MAFA was first formed in 1989 as the Fisheries Technicians
Association, but was renamed as the MAFA in 1994 for wider
participation by entrepreneurs and companies.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in both fresh water and sea fishery resources
with 8 million hectares of water such as lakes, rivers and
reservoirs, producing more than 240,000 tons of fresh water prawn
and fish annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
