<HEADLINE> Shanghai College Students Agree on Success Of China's Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A survey at 11 colleges and
universities in Shanghai Municipality on China's 20 years of
reforms and opening up recently showed that the majority of
college students there agree about the success.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 91 percent of those questioned believe
that China's economic strength had been greatly increased and the
economic restructuring a success; 90.3 percent recognized China's
new status in the international community and China is playing an
increasingly important role in international community; 81.1
percent hold that the food and clothing has been resolved and that
people are better off; 75.7 percent say that there has been a
marked improvement in science and education.
</P>
<P>
Many students say they are concerned about economic situation
after the 15th National Party Congress, but 52.1 percent think the
situation is healthy and stable; 65.4 percent say that the
macro-economic adjustments of the Central government are
appropriate and, nevertheless, 13.6 percent hold that
macro-control measures are a bit too tough.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead on to the next decade, those who were confident
or relatively optimistic made up 82.6 percent, and only 0.6
percent expressed a lack of confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
