<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Tries to Reduce Impact of Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis,
which has gripped the region for more than a year, has brought
about a rise in commodity prices, devaluation of local currency, a
drop in investment and close-down of a number of foreign and local
enterprises in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate, which stood at 16.2 percent before the
outbreak of the crisis in July 1997, increased sharply to 29.5
percent shortly after the outbreak. As a result, the value of the
Myanmar Kyat against the U.S. dollar fell from 160 per dollar at
the beginning of the crisis to 350 now.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in 1997 fell to 1.3 billion dollars from 2.3
billion dollar in 1996, and investment in the first six months of
this year were only 222 million dollars, according to official
statistics,
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that at least 65 companies have been
forced to close down since the outbreak of the crisis, out of
which 26 are foreign ones mainly from the Republic of Korea,
Singapore, Japan and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has hindered Myanmar's endeavors to achieve the
targeted growth of 6.4 percent in gross domestic product (GDP) in
fiscal 1997-98 ending in March, which only saw a GDP growth of 4.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Although the impact of the crisis on Myanmar is not seen as
serious as that on some other Southeast Asian countries which are
directly hit by the crisis, the government has taken measures to
prevent it from getting worse.
</P>
<P>
The government has called for boosting production in goods and
services, taking austere measures by cutting state expenses and
promoting export through production of import substitute goods and
export items to ensure hard currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, priority is being given to the building of mills
and factories which manufacture the designated goods for export.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, consumers in the country have also been urged
to use more home-made goods instead of foreign goods in face of
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Like some other member states of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) which are adopting a "sell more, buy less"
formula, Myanmar also called for importing less and exporting
more, and has shifted the priority tag from luxury items to more
essential ones.
</P>
<P>
The government has implemented a more efficient taxation system
and restricted import of certain categories of consumer goods,
especially non-essential imports, in an effort to prevent foreign
exchange reserves from draining.
</P>
<P>
To save its dwindling foreign exchange reserves, which stood
around 200 million dollars, Myanmar began controlling foreign
exchange payments from August 1997, limiting the payments for
imports, foreign remittances and overseas loans to 50,000 dollars
per month.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce the inflation rate, the central bank and
private banks have raised the annual interest rate from 12 percent
to 16 percent on bank savings and from 18 percent to 20 percent on
loans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar is trying to improve its investment
environment in order to attract more investors. It has approved
more projects, including those of industrial zones, for investors.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 17 industrial zones have been established in Myanmar
 including five in Yangon, with investment mainly from foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, on the other hand, is also trying to promote its
foreign trade, especially border trade by applying regular trade
procedures based on the U.S. dollar in place of local currencies.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate border trade, it has opened more trade points
with neighboring China and Thailand, increasing the number of such
points with China to six and with Thailand to five. More similar
points are expected to be added along the borders with Bangladesh
and India.
</P>
<P>
The government is considering granting special privileges to
local and foreign entrepreneurs who export goods worth 2 million
dollars or above through seaborne trade in the 1997-98 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
To promote trade activities, Myanmar has simplified its trade
formalities. Export and import licenses are issued within 48 hours
to traders instead of one week to one month.
</P>
<P>
The country promulgated in April this year new regulations for
import and export, designating 22 items of goods as priorities for
import.
</P>
<P>
To promote export, Myanmar has held various trade fairs in some
countries such as the Republic of Korea, Indonesia and the
Philippines to exhibit its products.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also held seminars with foreign trade organizations
including the Singapore Trade Development Board to find means for
export market development.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is also accelerating its privatization process as an
effort to reduce the impact of the regional financial crisis. The
privatization of state-owned economic enterprises (SEEs) is being
carried out in two phases.
</P>
<P>
The first phase, which is the privatization of all small-scale
SEEs, has been completed and the second phase, which deals with
about 1,760 medium- and larger-scale SEEs, is underway.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has said that it is ready to cooperate with other ASEAN
member states in resolving the regional financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
