<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Inflation Rate to Ease to 3.5 Percent Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's inflation rate next
year will ease to 3.5 percent compared with 8.1 percent this year,
the Commerce Ministry forecast.
</P>
<P>
The forecast implied that Thailand would continue to experience
tight-money conditions in 1999, according to the ministry's
Business Economics Department.
</P>
<P>
While an inflation rate of 3.5 percent was appropriate under
normal economic conditions, during a recession it merely reflected
declining purchasing power, Nateetip Tongkoa-on, director of the
department's trade and economic index division, was quoted
Wednesday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Officials said inflation would decline steadily during the
first half of 1999, after which it would increase slightly.
</P>
<P>
The 3.5 percent inflation forecast, which corresponded with one
made by the International Monetary Fund, was based on a number of
key assumptions. They included the baht stabilizing at 37 to the
U.S. dollar, interest rates remaining in the 13-14 percent range,
stable wages, and declining world oil prices, Nateetip said.
</P>
<P>
Inflation as measured by the Consumer Price Index (CPI) in the
first 11 months of this year rose by 8.4 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
But the year-on-year increase for November was just 4.7
percent. Compared with October, the rate declined by 0.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
