<HEADLINE> 2 U.K. Firms Withdraw From Chilean Fair Over Pinochet Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Two leading British companies
were conspicuously absent from Tuesday's opening of Chile's first
international naval fair for fear of retaliation by supporters of
former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet, now detained in London.
</P>
<P>
The Smith Industries and British Aerospace, which withdrew from
the Exponaval '98, are developing a mini-satellite with the
Chilean Air Force, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
Britain's frigate HMS Sutherland sailed back home last weekend
on warnings from the Chilean navy that it could not guarantee the
safety of the ship or her crew following a British court ruling
that denied Pinochet immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The former Chilean leader was put under house arrest in a
London clinic last month after a Spanish judge demanded his
extradition to Madrid to face charges of genocide, torture and
terrorism during his 14-year rule.
</P>
<P>
The incident fueled tensions in Chile's relations with Britain
and Spain.
</P>
<P>
However, eight other British companies are taking part in the
fair, along with Spain's Bazan firm, which is building a
Scorpene-type submarine for Chile with the French company DCN.
</P>
<P>
One billion U.S. dollars worth of business deals are expected
to be signed during the five-day fair, opened by Chilean President
Eduardo Frei in the port city of Valparaiso, 120 kilometers west
of Santiago.
</P>
<P>
A total of 84 companies from 15 countries are taking part in
the fair, including Aerospatiale, Eurocopter, Boston Whaler,
Sippican, Bazan, DCN, Raython, SIMA and the Chilean firm Asmar.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France are the main participants, while China,
Mexico and five other Latin American countries have been invited
as observers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
