<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Opposition Slammed for Pro-Rebels Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Lakshman Kadirgamar slammed the main opposition United Nation
Party (UNP) for its members' pro-rebels remarks, parliamentary
sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar Tuesday evening told the Parliament that the UNP was
representing the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels in
the Parliament, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The UNP had said that the LTTE was an invincible organization.
The UNP's arguments were almost for the LTTE and they were trying
to show how nice and brave the Tamil rebels were, Kadirgamar was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the United States has declared the LTTE as a
terrorist organization because it is in fact a terrorist outfit
and not a liberation movement.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 15-year war against the government
for a separate Tamil state in the country. More than 55,000 people
have been reportedly killed in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
The government could not forgive the LTTE rebels for what they
were doing to their own people but the UNP MPs, in particular
Anura Bandaranaike and A.C.S. Hameed, were saying they should rush
to negotiations with "a pack of murderers," the sources quoted
Kadiragamar as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the government would negotiate with the LTTE in
the context of recent LTTE statements that it was ready for talks,
the minister declined to answer at the moment, the sources said.
</P>
