<HEADLINE> NBA Players, Owners to Meet Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- With time running out, NBA
owners and the players' union today agreed to hold a bargaining
session Thursday that could save the season -- or cancel it.
</P>
<P>
Having apparently mended the hard feelings that forced them to
cancel Saturday's session, a league spokesman said negotiators of
owners and players will meet again, still far apart on the major
issues of revenue distribution, cost certainty and the timing
issues on the signing of free agents.
</P>
<P>
With the lockout in its 154th day, the sides have very little
time to reach an agreement and play an abbreviated season of
55-60 games. Although NBA commissioner David Stern has yet to
target a date on which the season would have to be canceled, many
believe the sides have just 10 days or so to reach a deal.
</P>
<P>
"If they don't have an agreement within the next two weeks,
the season's over," said one agent, whose clients include two
player representatives.
</P>
<P>
The last meeting was canceled as the union claimed the league
was "playing mind games" and the NBA accused the union of making
"a mockery" of collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation was a tremendous setback because the previous
session on November 20 had produced the most progress. 
</P>
