<HEADLINE> U.S.-Palestinian Commission Convenes First Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Tuesday
opened the first meeting of a joint commission similar to those
set up for state-to-state contacts.
</P>
<P>
Albright told the commission that the United States and the
Palestinian Authority should expand trade through a plan to allow
duty-free access for Palestinian goods, a U.S. official said
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said the commission met
for about an hour on subjects including trade development,
assistance projects, cultural and scientific exchanges, and
programs to develop good governance.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. insists that it is up to the Israelis and Palestinians
to agree on the future status of the Palestinian territories,
which now have internal autonomy under a strict Israeli control of
all the borders.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want an independent state, which is opposed by
the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
According to Rubin, the U.S.-Palestinian joint commission could
also help promote private-sector investment in the Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
Delegates agreed to meet again some time in January but did not
fix the venue or date, he said.
</P>
<P>
The commission grew out of the Wye River agreement between
Israel and the Palestinians, which was signed in Washington on
October 23 under U.S. auspices.
</P>
<P>
"It is what it is.... It is designed to build stronger ties
between the Palestinian Authority and the U.S. government," said
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Rubin criticized Arafat for his latest statements on declaring
an independent Palestinian state in May next year.
</P>
<P>
"It has been our position and remains our position that
unilateral actions or unilateral statements of that kind are not
helpful," he told a daily briefing.
</P>
<P>
At a donors' conference in Washington on Monday, the
U.S. promised the Palestinian Authority an extra 400 million
U.S. dollars on top of a regular grant of about 100 million
dollars a year. 
</P>
