<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changing Clan-Chief System of the Shui People (1) (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series-Part 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Editor's Note: Following is the
second of a series of stories featuring the fast-changing life and
culture of China's Zhuang, Miao, Yao, Shui and seven other main
ethnic groups in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region,
which will mark its 40th founding anniversary on December 11:
</P>
<P>
The old clan-chief system that is still practised by the more
than 300,000 members of the Shui ethnic group has begun taking on
a modern look. The Shui are one of 11 ethnic groups who have
inhabited Guangxi for generations.
</P>
<P>
The clan chief of Longtou Township is 80-year-old Peng Ruiyu.
He said that he was elected fifth clan chief of his village 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the customs, when the chief is in poor health or
dies, a new one is elected, Peng explained. "Everyone from the
Shui ethnic group will come for the election, during which a
candidate is named. If there is no objection, people will
shout 'yes' several times. No ballot is need, or a single hand
raised."
</P>
<P>
Longtou Township has about 400 Shui people with the surname
"Peng" who are believed to come from the same ancestor, who came
from neighboring Guangdong Province, according to the chief. They
also have their own language, but it has no written form.
</P>
<P>
Before the founding of New China in 1949, the Shui people
practised collective-gathering and equal distribution, legacies of
a primitive society.
</P>
<P>
Peng explained that the primary duty of a clan chief is to help
bring clan members in resolving disputes within the clan or with
neighboring ethnic groups, to live together harmoniously.
</P>
<P>
Another task is to pass on the history of the Shui to younger
generations and to sort out the clan genealogy.
</P>
<P>
Peng has a primary school education. His grandson is a
university student majoring in electronics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thompson Improves 100m Butterfly World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Olympic gold medalist Jenny
