<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Ethnic Group Series (Part 2): </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shui People (2)
</P>
<P>
With the great changes in recent years, the work of the clan
chief has also been changing. The use of a village committee has
broken the monopoly in decision making held by the chief. But,
according to Peng, the village committee talks every important
decision over with him first.
</P>
<P>
When differences arise, the committee will consider the
decision and then discuss it again with the chief. "The principle
is to take the interests of the majority into consideration," Peng
said.
</P>
<P>
In the past, most of his time was spent resolving clan matters,
but now he deals with affairs of the whole village. In the past, old
clan rules were something to stick to. Now legislation and the
spirit of the age are taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
A young member of the clan with the surname Peng fell in love
with a girl also surnamed Peng, but from another village.
According to the old rules, people with the same surname could not
marry. But, the chief asked, "Are you confident about marrying
each other? If so, just go ahead with it."
</P>
<P>
At the chief's home, there is a television set and a set of
couplets he wrote to mark the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
But, when asked to comment on the recently introduced ballot
system to elect village officials, the chief said, "The system is
good in the modern sense, of course. But the choice of clan chief
is different from the method for village officials."
</P>
<P>
Peng was appointed a member of the county committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference a few years
ago. When asked to comment on the possibility that the clan-chief
system may eventually vanish, he said, "It doesn't matter if there
is no clan chief, just as long as there are honest and upright
people who can help mediate disputes."
</P>
<P>
In any case, the eight Communist party members and village
officials all respect the clan chief, because they know the system
is an ethnic custom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Warns of Possible Rapid Spread of AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Health Minister Leonard
Solis warned here Tuesday that AIDS could spread rapidly in the
country unless affective precautions were taken.
</P>
<P>
In his speech on World AIDS Day, the official said Albania was
facing a danger of rapid spread of AIDS due to a lack of
information on this disease, the great mobility of the population,
the large number of refugees abroad, rising prostitution and drug
abuse.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that 38 AIDS cases have been detected and
officially registered since the first AIDS case was reported in
1993 and most of them had died, adding that the actual number of
AIDS patients is likely to be between 10 to 100 times the reported
figure, according to an estimate by experts.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged Albanians to fight AIDS, called on the
government to work out a complete anti-AIDS program and strengthen
the education so that each citizen would get to know how to avoid
HIV-inspection and fight drug taking.
</P>
<P>
Solis also called for equal treatment of AIDS victims,
maintaining secrecy for them, providing them with medical aid and
preventing them from intentionally spreading the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
