<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maonan People: an Ethnic Group with a Population of 70,000 (1) (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Editor's Note: Starting from
today, we'll release a series of stories featuring the
rapidly-changing life and culture of the 11 ethnic groups,
including Zhuang, Miao, Yao, Maonan and Gin, living in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, which will mark its 40th
founding anniversary on December 11. This is the first of the
serial stories:
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast to China's 1.2 billion people of the Han
nationality, the Maonan nationality, an ethnic group with a
population of only 70,000, remains unknown to many in the country.
</P>
<P>
"While everybody in our county knows the Han people, many of
our Han compatriots in Beijing may have no idea of who we are,"
said Tan Sanchuan, magistrate of Huanjiang Maonan Autonomous
County in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. "This can but only
enhance the awareness of our own existence."
</P>
<P>
Huanjiang County is the only Maonan autonomous county in the
country, where over 50,000 Maonan people live.
</P>
<P>
However, when in the county town, visitors find architecture
and dressing style identical to those in any town in south
China. Due to the strong influence of the Han culture, Maonan
people even use Han names.
</P>
<P>
"It's an imperative task to preserve our own tradition and
culture. Otherwise you may not be able to find any Maonan people
when revisiting our county," said Meng Guorong, a Maonan writer.
</P>
<P>
Meng, 58, has spent 20 years to collate and collect the folk
songs, anecdotes, and customs and habits of the Maonan people. One
of his books, describing the promise-fulfilling ritual of the
Maonan people, was recently collected by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
The ritual is held by the Maonan people for thanking the favor
given by divinities. During the ceremony, a sacrificial altar is
put up and the local people, dressed up as divinities, are singing
and dancing in accompany of different musical instruments for
three days and two nights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
