<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maonan People: an Ethnic Group with a Population of 70,000 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is said only 60 to 70 percent of the Maonan customs and
habits are still in practice today, and many of them can only be
found in remote rural areas, and they attract scholars and
researchers from Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The ancestors of the Maonan people belonged to a branch of the
ancient Baiyue people, whose activities can be traced back to the
Stone Age.
</P>
<P>
The Maonan population were a minimal 18,000 in 1953 and has
grown to 70,000 today. The Maonan language is considered the most
important bond to keep a sense of integrity of the ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
"One of the highest goals of our family is to teach our child
to speak the Maonan language," said Lei Hong, deputy director of
the county's Culture Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Lei is of the She ethnic group while her husband is
Maonan."Since we have to speak mandarin at home, it affects the
child's command of the Maonan language," Lei said.
</P>
<P>
Tan Song, a Maonan boy, said that classes in his primary school
are taught in Maonan.
</P>
<P>
According to Qin Shengmin, an ethnology scholar, the awakening
of the ethnic consciousness has become a world phenomenon. In
China, the introduction of market economy has enhanced such
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
"Without a strong sense of identity, an ethnic group will not
be able to compete with its counterparts and develop itself," Qin
said.
</P>
<P>
In Huanjiang County's Xianan Township, there is a huge group of
ancient tombs accommodating hundreds of outstanding ancestors of
the Maonan people, where memorial ceremonies are often held.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the township raised money for the maintenance of the
tombs and designated them a historical site under special
protection.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the township has built mineral ore plants and
developed beef cattle breeding in its bid to boost the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
"An ethnic group has to rely on a strong economy to invigorate
itself. Without adequate financial strength, how can we be capable
to preserve our culture?" said Tan Feng, a township official.
</P>
<P>
"If it were twenty years ago, when the Maonan people could
hardly feed themselves, nothing was possible," said writer Meng
Guorong.
</P>
<P>
According to Meng, at that time, the promise-fulfilling ritual
was labelled as a "feudalist superstition" and banned.
</P>
<P>
In its support to develop the ethnic economy and culture, the
central government has listed a program to collect and collate the
Maonan cultural legacy as a key State project.
</P>
<P>
The central government has also decided to provide financial
aids in the building of the first museum of the Maonan nationality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Provides Aid for Landmine Destruction in 7 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Tuesday that it
will provide 2.8 million Canadian dollars (1.8 million U.S.
dollars) for landmine destruction projects in Croatia, Chad,
Jordan, Kosovo of Yugoslavia, Mozambique, Ukraine and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The announcement marks the first anniversary of the Convention
on the Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling, Production and
Transfer of Anti-Personnel Mines and on their Destruction, known
as the Ottawa Convention, which opened for signature on December
3, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Just one year ago when 122 countries signed the Ottawa
Convention, it was recognized as an outstanding global
achievement, and we have made even more progress in the past 12
months," said Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Canada has played an important role in realizing this progress
through its contributions to numerous mine-action projects
worldwide, added the minister.
</P>
<P>
A total of 133 countries have signed the Ottawa Convention, and
55 of those have ratified it. The Convention will come into legal
force in March 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
