<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ideological Purification is Emphasized under Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A recent study has found that
the Chinese are paying more attention to ideological strength while
trying to make money.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred people at the Revolutionary Martyrs Cemetery on
Gele Mountain in the city of Chongqing recently were a part of a
3-day study by the cemetery's administration and the Department of
Journalism at Southwest University of Political Science and Law.
</P>
<P>
They found that 83.3 percent of the visitors made the special
trip to pay their respects to the martyrs for their sacrifice for
China's future and found it "very moving"; 93.3 percent said that
it helped purify their minds and caused them to think; and 79.3
percent answered 'yes' when asked whether they "still need this
idealism in the market economy".
</P>
<P>
The cemetery in the northwestern suburbs of Chongqing,
commemorates 300 people who were massacred by Kuomintang
reactionaries before New China was founded in 1949. A popular
novel "The Red Crag" is based on their struggle and sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that the spirit of the martyrs in sacrificing
their lives for mankind's future should be honored under the
socialist market economy, according to Li Hua, the director of the
Cemetery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
