<HEADLINE> Major Changes about Next World Cup May Happen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 2002 World Cup finals, co-hosted by Japan and South Korea,
may be three days shorter than this year's 33-day soccer gala in
France, Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that 30-day World Cup competition would be OK
because the first phase will be played in two countries.
</P>
<P>
If reschedule the traditional June-July dates, the World Cup
finals may avoid the rainy season in June-July in the two
co-hosting countries, Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi on
Tuesday, Blatter said he would endeavour to make the first World
Cup in the new millennium a big success.
</P>
<P>
There was no predecessor that FIFA awarded a World Cup to two
countries, so FIFA is faced with a difficult task, Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
The co-hosting Japan and South Korea and 1998 World Cup
champion France will gain berth automatically. FIFA must
re-allocate the remaining number of qualifying positions from the
six confederations.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday and Friday, this will be decided by the FIFA
executive committee in Zurich, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said FIFA would discuss the possibility that the
Democratic People's Repubic of Korea may host some games, howeve
r, it depends on the political situation.
</P>
<P>
Blatter arrived in Japan on Monday after ending a two-day
visit to South Korea. He visited the two countries for the first
time since he was elected the head of the world soccer governing
body, succeeding former president Havelange who had been in
office for 24 years. 
</P>
