<HEADLINE> Cuba Launches Anti-AIDS Education Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Cuba on Tuesday launched an AIDS
education campaign with the opening of a national center for
sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
The center, opened on World AIDS Day, will cater to young
Cubans, among whom AIDS cases have registered a significant
increase in recent years, center director Doctor Rosaida Ochoa
said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,120 people, including six children, have been
diagnosed with AIDS, while 570 have died and 598 currently have
full blown AIDS in Cuba, according to the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,500 Cubans are HIV-positive, with 531 of them receiving
health care as outpatients and the rest being treated in 13
special clinics.
</P>
<P>
The epidemiology director of the Health Ministry, Manuel
Santon, said Cuba had one of the lowest AIDS rates in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
