<HEADLINE> Latin Americans Discuss Sugar Industry Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Latin American and
Caribbean sugar producers started a meeting in Mexico City on
Tuesday to discuss strategies to head off a worldwide slump in the
market.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario Green opened the meeting of 23
members of the Geplacea group of sugar exporters, who together
make up 30 percent of the world output and 45 percent of exports.
</P>
<P>
Latin American and Caribbean sugar producers generate nearly
three million jobs.
</P>
<P>
In her opening speech, Green recognized the "serious downward
trend" of world prices, adding that large inventories and an
expected production growth "further darkened" the sector's
prospects.
</P>
<P>
The Geplacea group is headed by Luis Eduardo Zedillo, brother
of Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo. 
</P>
