<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Province Trying To Save Coral Reefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANYA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The coral souvenirs that used to
be so popular with tourists on China's island province of Hainan
are hardly seen any longer thanks to provincial efforts to protect
the coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
The city of Sanya attracts hundreds of thousands of visitors
each year. But, the coral reefs around the island has been
seriously affected over the past 30 years. Recent statistics show
that the reefs have shrunk to 480 kilometers in length from 1,200
kilometers in the 1960s. And, the area covered by coral has
declined by 50 percent to about 22,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Hainan took action to save the coral in August, closing down
130 coral lime kilns and 4 workshops processing coral crafts.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials say that they have had some success since
the rules on protecting of coral reefs were adopted in Hainan, but
local protectionism and some profit-motivated people are still a
problem in enforcing the rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
