<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Lowers Cash Rate by 0.25 Percentage Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Australia
(RBA), the country's central bank, announced Wednesday that it had
eased monetary policy, reducing the cash rate by 25 basis points
to 4.75 percent in a bid to boost the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
A fall in cash rate, the interest rate on overnight loans made
between institutions in the money market, would lead to cuts in
other interest rates, including banks' lending interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the move, Ian Macfarlane, governor of the central
bank, said the past year had seen an unusual degree of turmoil in
international financial markets, but the underlying trend in the
international economy had been towards lower growth, lower
inflation and lower world interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Australia's economy grew by 3.9 percent during the financial
year of 1997-1998, which ended on June 30, 1998, and the federal
government predicted that the growth rate for the current
financial year would be 2.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
"With a significant decline in world growth predicted by most
forecasters, it is still likely that growth in Australia will
slow, at least temporarily, during 1999," the governor said.
</P>
<P>
"In the medium term, Australian monetary policy aims to achieve
an average inflation rate of somewhere between 2 and 3 percent.
Inflation has recently been running below 2 percent, but our
forecasts point to some further pick-up."
</P>
<P>
The rate cut brought Australia's interest rate into line with
other countries which recently eased monetary policy, including
the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
The RBA last reduced interest rates by half a percentage point
to 5 percent on July 30, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
