<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Energy Base Near China's Bohai Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- China is increasing work on a
port geared to power generation and oil exploration on the
northern edge of Bohai Bay in Suizhong, a strategic point between
Beijing and the three provinces in northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
An offshore oilfield with 300 million tons of reserves was
discovered 70 km from Suizhong in 1992, putting the small town in
the limelight.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the country has spent 6 billion yuan setting
up a dozen oil drilling rigs and a dock in Suizhong.
</P>
<P>
Work on a thermal power plant is also under way. The first
phase, costing 11 billion yuan, has two generating units, each
with a capacity of 800,000 kw to be imported from Russia. The
first generating unit will start operation in June 1999 and the
second in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The energy base has attracted a group of overseas investors who
have gone to Suizhong to do studies or hold business
negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
