<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remittances by Filipino Overseas Workers to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Despite the lingering regional
financial crisis, at least 1.8 billion U.S. dollars are expected
to be infused into the Philippine economy in the fourth quarter of
this year by overseas Filipino workers, an official said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star Wednesday quoted Bienvenido Laguesma,
secretary of the Department of Labor and Employment, as saying
that remittances peak twice a year, in June, when schools open in
the country and in December, the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
The fourth quarter contributions comprise about 30 percent of
the yearly total, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that for the past five years, remittances by 4.5
million overseas Filipino workers average 6 billion dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
The remittances saved the economy from the much feared
recession as the country's gross national product posted a 0.8
percent growth for the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
At least 50,000 to 60,000 Filipino overseas workers return home
for the Christmas season, the secretary said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
