<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Tuesday he had
waived until October 21, 1999, certain sanctions against India and
Pakistan imposed after they conducted a series of nuclear tests in
May.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of a visit by Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
to the U.S., the White House released a letter from Clinton
ordering that the sanctions, which affect lending by the U.S.
Export-Import Bank, the Overseas Private Investment Corp. and the
Trade and Development Agency, be waived. (US-Pakistan-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Tuesday it will
declassify and make public documents relating to human rights
abuses during the rule of former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
"The administration is conducting a review of documents in its
possession that may shed light on human rights abuses during the
Pinochet era," said State Department spokesman James Rubin.
(US-Pinochet-Document)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler
had asked Iraq to hand over immediately a document seen at its Air
Force headquarters in July, according to a letter released here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz over
the weekend, Butler, Executive Chairman of the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, said Iraq should hand over a copy of
the document by November 30. But there was no sign the document
has arrived. (Butler-Iraq-Document) 
</P>
