<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro-Zone Annual Inflation Stable: EU Statistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The annual inflation rate for
the euro-zone remained stable at one percent between September and
October this year, compared with 1.5 percent a year earlier, the
European Union (EU) said in a report released here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the 15 EU countries' annual inflation
rate, which had stood at 1.7 percent a year earlier, fell from 1.2
percent in September to 1.1 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the inflation rate in the United States remained at
1.5 percent, fell to zero in Switzerland and rose to 0.2 percent
in Japan. But the report said that these indices are not strictly
comparable with the European harmonized indices.
</P>
<P>
The overall picture indicates healthy economic fundamentals in
the 11-nation euro-zone for introducing the single currency on
January 1 next year, which is on a 31-day countdown from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the EU is making final preparations in its third
stage of economic monetary union by implementing harmonized
economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The member states are also working to bring down the average
budget deficit from around 5.5 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) to around 2.5 percent during a period of relatively
slack economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
