<HEADLINE> Tyson Faces up to 20 Years in Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson admitted he lost
his temper following a traffic accident and the former
heavyweight champion faces up to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
Tyson pleaded no contest today to charges he assaulted two
men. Although the plea is not an admission of guilt, he still is
likely to be sentenced 10 years on each count.
</P>
<P>
"He admits to losing his temper on the side of the road,"
Tyson attorney Paul Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
Tyson told Judge Steven Johnson in Maryland that he was not
promised leniency and does not expect preferential treatment in
sentencing. He also said he was aware his plea could affect his
probation for a 1992 rape conviction in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
"The state was prepared to present the facts in the case,"
said Assistant State's Attorney Carol Crawford, objecting to
Johnson acceptance of the plea.
</P>
<P>
Abmielec Saucedo and Richard Hardick said Tyson kicked and
punched them following the accident on August 31 in suburban
Washington, D.C. They have reached an out-of-court settlement with
 Tyson to avoid a civil suit in the case.
</P>
<P>
"The complainants will testify at sentencing that this is the
appropriate plea," Kemp said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
