<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Indonesia's Quake Hits 32 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from the
powerful earthquake that rocked remote islands in Indonesia's
Maluku and North Sulawesi provinces climbed to at least 32 on
Tuesday as rescuers continued searching for more dead and injured.
</P>
<P>
Reports of more deaths and destruction came in from the western
side of Mangole island, Maluku province, and from Manado, capital
of North Sulawesi province.
</P>
<P>
Officials said 25 of the dead were found in Mangole, a
timber-producing island of 17,000 people that bore the brunt of
Sunday night's quake measuring 7.6 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said another seven people had died in
Manado.
</P>
<P>
"We are still looking for more victims", Sumadi, an official
with the Meteorology and Geophysics Agency in Jakarta, was quoted
by the Indonesian Observer Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Strong aftershocks continued to rock Mangole island on Tuesday,
hampering rescue efforts and frightening villagers.
</P>
<P>
Afraid that aftershocks might bring down their damaged homes,
about 7,000 people in Mangole slept in tents or in the open.
</P>
<P>
Local government official Wahab Konoras told reporters that at
least eight villagers were still missing on Tuesday. "Rescue teams
are looking for more possible victims in remote areas. The toll
could rise further," he added.
</P>
<P>
Widespread damage was also reported on neighboring Taliabu
island, but there were no reports of deaths there.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said over 150 people were injured and more
than 858 homes, churches, mosques and other buildings were damaged
on both islands. Mangole's main government buildings were
flattened.
</P>
<P>
Some houses slid into the sea. Roads were cut and bridges
destroyed, hampering search and rescue efforts, officials added.
</P>
</TEXT>
