<HEADLINE> U.S. Swimmer Gary Hall Allowed to Compete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Olympic gold medalist Gary
Hall was allowed to swim in an international meet despite a
marijuana-related suspension through December 12.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge Roger Strand, who issued a temporary
restraining order Monday allowing Hall to compete, stuck by his
earlier ruling, according to a report here.
</P>
<P>
FINA, internatinal swimming governing body, siad the
federation would not appeal. "We can do nothing more other than
obey the order," FINA secretary Gunnar Werner said today by phone.
</P>
<P>
"This decision is only valid in the United States. Hall is
still suspended in the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
Hall won gold medals as part of the U.S. 400-meter freestyle
and 400 medley relay teams in the 1996 Olympics. He also won
silver medals in the 50 and 100 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
He was scheduled to compete in today's World Cup competition
and later this week in the U.S. Open competition.
</P>
<P>
Hall was temporarily suspended in July after FINA said he
tested positive for marijuana during a May 15 competition. During
a November 6 hearing, Hall received his three-month suspension
from FINA's drug panel. FINA then deducted two of the three
months already served by Hall during the temporary suspension,
which left him with 30 more days to serve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
