<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Venture Developing Battery-Operated Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A business venture in Tibet has
announced that it is investing in battery-operated cars using a
new curved surface lead-acid storage battery.
</P>
<P>
Gao Xiang, chairman of the board of the Hebang New Power
Technology Research Institute, says that his company and Sichuan
Hebang Power Investment Corporation will put 250 million yuan (30
million U.S. dollars) into 2 production centers for the new
batteries to be built in Lhasa, the capital of Tibet, and Chengdu,
the capital of Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
He says the battery-operated cars are expected to put on the
market within three years. A car that seats 4 people can go at a
speed of 100 kilometers per hour. The service life of the storage
battery is two years.
</P>
<P>
He says the retail price is expected to be less than 200,000
yuan, or 50,000 yuan more than for a gas-powered motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Gao says that the new battery recently obtained provincial level
appraisal and a patent on a recharge device has been applied for
in the United States and 8 other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
