<HEADLINE> Batty Pleads for Common Sense to Prevail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Wantaway midfielder David Batty
demanded "common sense" from Leeds and Newcastle in a bid to end
his transfer torment on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A frustrated Batty is currently in limbo as he anxiously waits
for the two clubs to reach a compromise on what he is worth, and
despite interest from several other Premiership clubs Batty has
made it clear it's Leeds or no one.
</P>
<P>
Elland Road chairman Peter Ridsdale has already bid four
million pounds for the England international, but the Magpies are
looking for another two million pounds.
</P>
<P>
Batty's decision to waive 800,000 pounds in signing-on bonuses
to rush through the move, money agreed when he recently signed a
new five-year deal, has cut little ice with the St James' Park
board.
</P>
<P>
With both clubs digging their heels in, the impasse could drag
on to the annoyance of Batty, who was hoping to have been back at
Leeds in time to celebrate his 30th birthday on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he turned up at Newcastle's Chester-le-Street
training headquarters on Tuesday morning, while advisor Hayden
Evans - who had cancelled all business appointments throughout
the last two days - waited for news.
</P>
<P>
But Evans said: "It has been very frustrating, but there's
nothing we can do. David has done all he can. He has gone public
with his transfer request and made his intentions perfectly
clear. You could say he has put his money where his mouth is.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously the two clubs are a bit apart in their valuations
and David is just hoping for a degree of common sense as both
clubs know exactly what he wants. I'm optimistic there is middle
ground. When you're a football agent you have to be an eternal
optimist. Hopefully there will be a compromise," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
