<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones, Godina Win Owens Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. female sprinter Marion
Jones and male shot putter John Godina won the Jesse Owens
Memorial Awards for 1998 today in Florida.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who was undefeated in the sprints in both 100 and 200
meters this year, won the award for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
She beat distance runner Regina Jacobs, middle distance runner
Jearl Miles-Clark, shot putter Connie Price-Smith, high jumper
Tisha Walker and race walker Joanne Dow.
</P>
<P>
Godina, the first thrower to receive the honor, beat hurdler
Bryan Bronson, high jumper Charles Austin, sprinter Maurice
Greene, distance runner Bob Kennedy to win the award.
</P>
<P>
They were chosen by athletics administrators, coaches and
member of the Track and Field Wirters of America.
</P>
<P>
Jones won 36 finals this season in the 60, 100, 200 and 400
meters. She lost her only long jump to Germany's Heike Drechsler
at the World Cup in Johannesbury, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
She ran the fastest times in the 100 and 200 in times of 10.65
and 21.62 seconds respectively, making her the No.2 performer in
history behind the late Florence Griffith Joyner.
</P>
<P>
She finished with times faster than 10.90 for 17 times, and
became the first woman in 50 years to win the 100, 200 and long
jump in the USA Championship history.
</P>
<P>
Godina won the shot put and discus events at the USA
Championships and remained unbeaten in all his 17 shotput
competitions.
</P>
<P>
The Owens Awards, named for the great Jesse Owens, will be
presented to Jones and Godina at a banquet Friday night at the
U.S Track &AMP; Field convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improper Diet Affecting Chinese Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Although China has successfully
provided most of its 1.2 billion people with adequate food,
improper diet in both urban and rural areas is affecting people's
health, said a nutritionist here today.
</P>
<P>
The consumption of meat in cities has sharply increased over
the past two decades, while fewer grains and vegetables are being
consumed, said Chen Chunming, a researcher at the Chinese Academy
of Preventive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
"A diet high in fat and caloric content causes cardiovascular
diseases and diabetes," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the incidence of high blood pressure among
Chinese adults has increased from 7.7 percent 20 years ago to
nearly 10 percent today, and the figure in large cities such as
Beijing is as high as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over 14 percent of Chinese urbanites over the age of 20 suffer
from obesity, according Chen.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicate that Chinese spent 41.9 billion yuan
(about five billion U.S. dollars) to treat diseases related to
improper diet, including cardiovascular diseases and obesity, in
1994. This figure is increasing at a rate of 17.7 percent, and is
projected to reach 126.1 billion yuan (15 billion dollars) in
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Chen also pointed out that malnutrition is very common among
Chinese village residents because of a lack of nutrition
information. About 13 million children under the age of six are
underweight and 24 million are below the standard height.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese nutritionists have recently published a diet
guidebook, and they say China should hasten the development of the
soybean industry to produce bean products with a high protein
content as a daily food for Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Chinese per capita milk consumption is only 6.4 percent of the
world average, and this low intake of calcium leads to high
incidence of rickets among infants, and osteoporosis among the
aged. Chinese should drink more milk and increase the variety of
milk products, say the nutritionists.
</P>
<P>
They also advise Chinese to eat less pork, which currently
accounts for 70 percent of all meat consumption, and eat more
chicken.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
