<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Waives Some Sanctions on Pakistan, India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday he had waived until October 21, 1999, certain
sanctions against India and Pakistan imposed after they conducted
a series of nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of a visit by Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
to the U.S., the White House released a letter from Clinton
ordering that the sanctions, which affect lending by the U.S.
Export-Import Bank, the Overseas Private Investment Corp. and the
Trade and Development Agency, be waived.
</P>
<P>
Last month, U.S. officials announced Clinton planned to take
the step, which will also allow U.S. banks to resume lending to
Pakistan and India because of progress in talks with the two
countries on arms issues.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's letter to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also
paves the way for international financial agencies to lend
Pakistan money to support an assistance program that it is
negotiating with the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The move will also allow military officers from the two
countries to receive U.S. training.
</P>
<P>
In October, the U.S. Congress gave Clinton limited authority to
waive some sanctions imposed on India and Pakistan after nuclear
tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
