<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Farm Incomes to Fall by 33 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- British farm incomes are
expected to go down by 33 percent this year, compared with 1997, a
government statement said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The fall in incomes during 1998 is due mainly to the fall in
prices for most major commodities," Farm Minister Nick Brown said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Farm incomes can be cyclical. Indeed they rose by 90 percent
between 1990 and 1995. It is now our task to work together towards
a sustainable, competitive and profitable industry," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The 33 percent fall represented a 35 percent fall in real terms
and was the second substantial fall in successive years, according
to the figures showed in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Total incomes from farming had fallen by 63 percent in real
terms over the past two years, although from an historically high
level, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
