<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Invests Heavily in Water Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province, a major grain
producer in east China, plans to invest 14.86 billion yuan in
water conservation projects to deal with its severe water shortage
and stabilize grain production.
</P>
<P>
These are projects backed by local funds instead of others
invested by the central government.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five decades, Shandong has constructed many
water conservation projects and has controlled soil erosion over
an area of more than 30,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the province has 4.66 million hectares of irrigated
farmland including over 3.33 million hectares able to produce good
harvests under all weather conditions, and grain production
capacity there now exceeds 40 billion kilos.
</P>
<P>
The province still faces severe water shortages, as its
per-capita water resource is only one-sixth of the national
average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
