<HEADLINE> U.S., Mozambique Sign Investment Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Mozambique Tuesday signed a bilateral investment treaty that set
the stage for increased U.S. investment in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was signed by U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky and Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano, who is on a
five-day official visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We have very many American companies who are interested in
further investment in Mozambique," said Gayle Smith, a National
Security Council expert on Africa.
</P>
<P>
In addition, U.S. Agency for International Development Director
Brian Atwood signed an agreement granting Mozambique 66 million
U.S. dollars for development and humanitarian needs.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton and Chissano met for 40 minutes at the
White House and they discussed ways to resolve problems that may
arise in Mozambican parliamentary and presidential elections
scheduled for next October.
</P>
<P>
The United States will provide Mozambique 1 million U.S.
dollars to help organize its elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
