<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-01 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 1 Million Iraqi Students Fail to Enroll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Over 1 million Iraqi students,
or 20 percent of the total number of students expected to attend
schools, have failed to enroll in 1998, said Iraqi Education
Minister Fahad al-Shokrah on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, nearly 200,000 school dropouts were recorded this
year, most of whom are primary and secondary students, al-Shokrah
said in an exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem of school dropouts worsened due to the
impact of the U.N. embargo on Iraqi people's income as well as the
people's weakened belief in the benefits of education, another
effect of the prolonged sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that before the U.N. sanctions, the Iraqi
government provided students with all the necessary requirements
for education, such as books, stationery and scientific equipment
and laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions brought about acute shortage of stationery in
Iraq's primary and secondary schools. For example, the country
needs a total of 75 million notebooks for its students, but only
25 million are available, he said.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions were imposed on Iraq following
its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, which touched off the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Under the fourth phase of the oil-for-food program which
expired a week ago, Iraq was allowed to export 5.2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shokrah said that of the 5.2 billion dollars, 38 million
dollars were allocated for the education sector, which means less
than two dollars for each student per month.
</P>
<P>
Before the U.N. sanctions, however, 500 million dollars were
allocated for the education sector every year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,100 schools were destroyed during the 1991 Gulf War, and
rebuilding these schools requires millions of dollars, said
al-Shokrah.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq's population have increased, but no new schools have been
built, therefore all the schools are over-crowded, and this will
inevitably affect the quality of education," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was awarded an international trophy, before the sanction,
for its efforts in eradicating illiteracy, Al-Shokrah noted, but
illiteracy is making a rapid comeback in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The number of teaching staff is dropping at an average rate of
10 percent a year after the imposition of U.N. sanctions, as a
result, illiteracy rate is increasing at an average rate of about
5 percent every year," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The monthly salary of a primary school teacher is 3,500 Iraq
dinars, or less than three U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the U.N. trade embargo is lifted one day, its
influence will remain for the many generations to come," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
