<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German-French Summit disagrees on EU Farm And Bonn Rebate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of France and Germany
ended a two-day summit Tuesday with discord over trimming costly
European Union farm subsidies and German demands for a EU budget
rebate.
</P>
<P>
But "the differences of opinion are small", said French
President Jacques Chirac at a joint press conference with German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroede after the summit, seeking to play down
disagreement between Bonn and Paris over how to cut EU agriculture
spending which gobbles half of the bloc's annual budget.
</P>
<P>
Germany wants a major cut in its EU membership bill through
shifting responsibility for farm subsidies to individual member
states. France opposes this.
</P>
<P>
France is also a major beneficiary of agriculture subsidies
from EU, according to DPA.
</P>
<P>
Bonn is by far the EU's biggest paymaster with annual net
contributions of over 12.4 billion dollars, compared with just
0.47 billion dollars for France.
</P>
<P>
Both Schroeder and Chirac underscored their caution on swift EU
expansion into the former East Bloc.
</P>
<P>
"It is certainly true, this process will take longer than
planned," said Chirac. Bonn and Paris agreed the EU would have to
reform its own institutions before taking in new members, he said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder agreed: "It is difficult to set a date" for
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder also stressed that reforming EU before enlargement
would be "difficult" given sharp disagreement over how to downsize
the European Commission and shift from the current voting system -
which allows one member to block decisions - to majority voting.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he predicted reform issues linked to the
so-called Agenda 2000 - reforming farm subsidies, the E.U. budget
and structural aid policies - would be hammered out by a special
summit to be held in Germany next March.
</P>
<P>
Both Schroeder and Chirac agreed also EU unemployment should be
fought with "binding" employment targets and called on the
15-nation Union to approve an "employment pact" at its December
11-12 Vienna summit.
</P>
<P>
On NATO, Schroeder told reporters that Germany would remain a
firm member of the alliance regardless of how a debate was
resolved on whether to retain the possible first-use of nuclear
weapons as part of NATO strategy.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Green foreign minister Joschka Fischer has called for
NATO to eliminate any first-use option for nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Potsdam summit was also attended by French Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin and some 20 cabinet ministers from both nations. The
semi-annual meeting has been a cornerstone of the Franco-German
axis since the 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
