<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, December 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's naval and air forces on Monday evening
launched military exercises in the Persian Gulf, an Iranian
military official announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The four-day maneuvers, codenamed "Shahamat" (Bravery), were
designed to improve the combat readiness of the forces and assess
the capabilities of parachutists and commandos, head of the
operational command of the exercises Ali Razmjoo said.
(BC-Iran-Maneuvers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The newly elected Lebanese President Emile Lahoud on
Tuesday is set to hold a new round of consultations with
parliament to find a new candidate for prime minister after
outgoing Rafik Hariri refused to remain in his post,
</P>
<P>
There is wide speculation here that the 69-year-old veteran
politician Salim Hoss will be charged with the task of forming a
new government. (BC-Lebanon-PM-Designation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A member of the Israeli allied South Lebanon Army
(SLA) was killed and another wounded in two separate roadside
bombs in south Lebanon Tuesday, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Both blasts occurred on roads in Jezzine, an area controlled by
SLA outside the Israeli occupied zone in south Lebanon, the radio
added.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attacks. It said in a statement that an SLA
member was killed when he stepped down on a roadside bomb it
planted. (BC-Lebanon-SLA)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Members of an Israeli peace group Tuesday clashed
with the police in the controversial Har Homa construction area in
east Jerusalem as they tried to halt a bidding tour on the site.
</P>
<P>
The clashed took place as several Israeli contractors
interested in Har Homa building project toured the site in a
convoy of cars, reported the Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen Peace Now Movement members protesting against the
construction plan tried to approach the site but were stopped by
the police. (BC-Israel-Settlements)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Over 1 million Iraqi students, or 20 percent of the
total number of students expected to attend schools, have failed
to enroll in 1998, said Iraqi Education Minister Fahad al-Shokrah
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, nearly 200,000 school dropouts were recorded this
year, most of whom are primary and secondary students, al-Shokrah
said in an exclusive interview with Xinhua. (BC-Iraq-Education)
</P>
