<HEADLINE> U.S. Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rebounded
on Tuesday from an extended plunge in the morning, with the Dow
Jones industrial average up 16.99 to 9133.54 at the closing.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip index fell 216.53 points on Monday amid
profit-taking from previous gains, notably a 214.72 surge a week
before, which boosted the index to its peak of 9374.27.
</P>
<P>
The Dow dipped 128 points before it reversed at noon. Most of
other market indicators also turned into a positive territory.
</P>
<P>
The market mood ignored big name acquisitions such as the case
in which top U.S. oil company Exxon agreed on Tuesday to buy Mobil
in a 77 billion U.S. dollar deal to create the world's largest
energy company and a 10.1 billion dollar takeover of Bankers Trust
by Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
Based on preliminary data, the technology-laced Nasdaq
composite index rose 54.21 to 2003.75 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 rose 11.65 to 1175.28.
</P>
<P>
On the New York Stock Exchange, decliners led advancers by a
slim margin with trading volume up to 781 million shares from 685
million previously. 
</P>
