<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Expects 2.5 PCT Growth in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank expects
real economic growth in western Europe to reach just 2.5 percent
next year, ECB President Wim Duisenberg said on Tuesday following
a meeting of top ECB officials in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The figure for 1998 was expected to be 3.0 percent, also below
original expectations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the ECB chief, the fact that the situation on the
world finance and currency markets had calmed down recently was a
positive development. Nevertheless, confidence among companies,
especially in western Europe, had slipped.
</P>
<P>
He called on all parties involved to continue their moderate
wage and salary policies, because this was a prerequisite for
maintaining competitiveness and profitability, thereby leading to
increased investment and employment.
</P>
<P>
Governments should also stick to strict stability in their
budgetary policies, Duisenberg said. 
</P>
