<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Experiences 4th Abnormal Autumn in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- This past autumn has turned
out to be one of the most humid and least sunny seasons in
Belgium, the Belgian Royal Meteorological Institute said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The months of September, October and November have experienced
an accumulated rainfall of 355 millimeters compared with a past
average of 208 millimeters while the accumulated sun-shine for the
same period was 234 hours compared with the past average of 325
hours.
</P>
<P>
The much humidity and little sun-shine combined to contribute
toward a lower-than-usual temperature in the three months,
according to meteorologists at the institute.
</P>
<P>
The average minimum temperature of this period was 0.7 degrees
Celsius as against the previous reading of 3.5 degrees; the
average mean temperature was 3.7 degrees compared with the
previous reading of 6.6 degrees, while the average maximum
temperature was 6.6 degrees, 2.3 degrees lower than than the
previous reading.
</P>
<P>
This past autumn, therefore, has been registered as the fourth
most humid and least sunny season in the country's history ever
since the royal meteorological institute started recording weather
conditions in 1833.
</P>
<P>
With a rainfall of 411 millimeters, the autumn of 1974 is the
most humid autumn in Belgium while the least sun-shined autumn was
recorded in 1887 when sun-shine totaled only 194 hours in three
months.
</P>
<P>
The unusual rainfall this past autumn caused some flooding in
eastern and northeastern Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
