<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Fall to New Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- World oil markets on Tuesday
recorded fresh lows, as London's benchmark Brent closed at $10.21
a barrel, down 25 cents, after touching a new 12-year low of
$10.06.
</P>
<P>
Average prices for the year to date, at $13.60 a barrel, are
the lowest since 1976.
</P>
<P>
Dealers now fear that the reopening of old OPEC (Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries) rivalries at rancorous talks in
Vienna could signal a scrap for market share among the group's
biggest producers, rather than another round of the supply cuts
agreed earlier in the year, a Reuters report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, oil companies reacted to the price crash with a
series of deals which culminated on Tuesday with the biggest
industrial merger ever between U.S. Exxon and Mobil.
</P>
<P>
OPEC does not meet again until March by which time it will have
to have patched up some glaring differences if it wants to add to
the 2.6 million barrels daily of output cuts it made earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
The alternative, warn analysts, could be a lengthy period of
single-digit oil prices.
</P>
<P>
A basket of seven OPEC crudes was valued at $9.89 a barrel on
Monday, dipping into single digits for the first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Prices have also been hit in recent weeks by a slowdown in
global oil demand which in October was estimated running 1.5
million barrels a day lower than in the same month of 1997.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's best hope now, said analysts, would appear to be some
behind-the-scenes discussion of strategy and a cold winter in the
United States, the world's biggest importer, according to Reuters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
