<HEADLINE> Lesotho to Launch Interim Authority Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's Interim
Political Authority (IPA), tasked to prepare the country for
fresh elections, will be sworn in next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili made the
announcement at the end of a two-hour meeting of political party
leaders on Tuesday to consider the inauguration of the IPA, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili said South African President Nelson Mandela, who is
chairman of the Southern African Development Community (SADC),
will then arrange for the holding of the inaugural meeting of the
transitional body.
</P>
<P>
He said the Basutholand Congress Party (BCP) was the only one
of the 12 parties which participated in the May general elections
that had not yet submitted the names of their representatives on
the IPA.
</P>
<P>
The BCP leadership said the names of their nominees would be
forwarded to the minister of law by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
The IPA is supposed to be composed of two representatives from
each and every party.
</P>
<P>
The swearing in of the body had been delayed by the death of
the leader of the Basotho National Party (BNP), Everestus
Sekhonyana, who will be buried this week.
</P>
<P>
The BCP, the BNP and Marematlou Freedom Party are three major
opposition parties in the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the IPA was agreed upon by government and
opposition in mid-October following an agreement that new
elections would be held in 15 to 18 months' time.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy won the May
elections, but opposition parties claimed that they were rigged.
Protests began in the beginning of August and went out of control
in September, prompting military intervention by the SADC.
</P>
</TEXT>
