<DOCNO> XIE19981202.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Youth Accounts for Over Half of New AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Over half of new AIDS
infections in the world occur among young people because they are
an age group with special vulnerability to the fatal killer.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed at the national function which was held here
Tuesday to mark the World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
The documents distributed by Uganda AIDS Commission showed
that of all those infected after infancy, at least half are young
people. The 10 to 24 age group accounts for more than 30 percent
of all people in the developing world where the epidemic is
concentrated.
</P>
<P>
The documents attributed this high infection rate among young
people to inadequate education about sexuality issues, unsafe
sexual practices, existence of customary laws and practices such
as forced marriages, unsafe circumcision, substance abuse like
alcohol consumption and others.
</P>
<P>
Young women are biologically and socially more vulnerable to
HIV than young men because their reproductive tract is more
susceptible to infection.
</P>
<P>
They also face the problem of unwanted sex ranging from social
pressure, coercion by older men in authority or outright
violence.
</P>
<P>
As a result, in Uganda, the HIV infection in girls of 15 to 19
years is six times higher than in boys of the same age group.
</P>
<P>
Boys under the age of 18 are not protected by the laws of
sexual offences yet it is known that a number of them are sexually
abused by older women and men.
</P>
<P>
Alcohol consumption affects sexual behavior which increases
young people's vulnerability to HIV, the documents said.
</P>
<P>
Africa is the continent which suffers most from the pandemic.
Over 83 percent of deaths caused by AIDS is from sub-Sahara
Africa and 80 percent of new infections among children is in this
region.
</P>
<P>
With the tireless efforts by the government and
non-governmental organizations in this field, Uganda's infection
rate has dropped from 30 percent to 15 percent. Even this rate
is still unacceptably high.
</P>
<P>
The government is doing all it can to reduce the rate to a new
low and to find new remedies for the problem. 
</P>
